# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: affluence-in-the-united-states
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/2010-united-states-census] The **2010 United States census** was the 23rd United States census.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/2010-united-states-census] National Census Day, the reference day used for the census, was April 1, 2010.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/2010-united-states-census] The census was taken via mail-in citizen self-reporting, with enumerators serving to spot-check randomly selected neighborhoods and communities.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/2010-united-states-census] As part of a drive to increase the count's accuracy, 635,000 temporary enumerators were hired.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/2010-united-states-census] The population of the United States was counted as 308,745,538, a 9.7% increase from the 2000 United States census.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/2010-united-states-census] This was the first census in which all states recorded a population of over 500,000 people as well as the first in which all 100 largest cities recorded populations of over 200,000.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/2010-united-states-census] It was the first census since 1930 that California did not record the largest population growth in absolute number.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/2010-united-states-census] Texas surpassed California's growth by 4.3 million to 3.4 million.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/2010-united-states-census] As required by the United States Constitution, the U.S.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/2010-united-states-census] Census has been conducted every 10 years since 1790.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/2010-united-states-census] The 2000 U.S. census was the previous census completed.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/2010-united-states-census] Census is required by law of people living in the United States in Title 13 of the United States Code.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/2010-united-states-census] On January 25, 2010, Census Bureau Director Robert Groves personally inaugurated the 2010 census enumeration by counting World War II veteran Clifton Jackson, a resident of Noorvik, Alaska.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/2010-united-states-census] More than 120 million census forms were delivered by the U.S.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/2010-united-states-census] The number of forms mailed out or hand-delivered by the Census Bureau was approximately 134 million on April 1, 2010.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/2010-united-states-census] The 2010 census national mail participation rate was 74%.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/2010-united-states-census] From April through July 2010, census takers visited households that did not return a form, an operation called "non-response follow-up" (NRFU).
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/2010-united-states-census] Census Bureau delivered population information to the U.S. president for apportionment, and later in March 2011, complete redistricting data was delivered to states.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/2010-united-states-census] Personally identifiable information will be available in 2082.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/2010-united-states-census] The Census Bureau did not use a long form for the 2010 census.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/2010-united-states-census] In several previous censuses, one in six households received this long form, which asked for detailed social and economic information.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/2010-united-states-census] Were there any additional people staying here on April 1, 2010, that you did not include in Question 1?
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/2010-united-states-census] What is Person 1's age and Person 1's date of birth?
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/2010-united-states-census] Is Person 1 of Hispanic, Latino, or Spanish origin?
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/2010-united-states-census] Does Person 1 sometimes live or stay somewhere else?
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/2010-united-states-census] The form included space to repeat some or all of these questions for up to twelve residents total.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/2010-united-states-census] In contrast to the 2000 census, an Internet response option was not offered, nor was the form available for download.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/2010-united-states-census] Detailed socioeconomic information collected during past censuses will continue to be collected through the American Community Survey.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/2010-united-states-census] The survey provides data about communities in the United States on a 1-year or 3-year cycle, depending on the size of the community, rather than once every 10 years.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/2010-united-states-census] A small percentage of the population on a rotating basis will receive the survey each year, and no household will receive it more than once every five years.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/2010-united-states-census] Census Bureau announced that it would count same-sex married couples.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/2010-united-states-census] However, the final form did not contain a separate "same-sex married couple" option.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/2010-united-states-census] When noting the relationship between household members, same-sex couples who are married could mark their spouses as being "Husband or wife", the same response given by opposite-sex married couples.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/2010-united-states-census] An "unmarried partner" option was available for couples (whether same-sex or opposite-sex) who were not married.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/2010-united-states-census] The Census 2010 Language Program was significantly expanded.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/2010-united-states-census] Language assistance in 49 languages in the 2000 Census was increased to 59 languages in Census 2000.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/2010-united-states-census] In addition to English, Census questionnaire was available in five non-English languages: Spanish, Chinese (simplified), Korean, Vietnamese, and Russian.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/2010-united-states-census] The 2010 census cost $13 billion, approximately $42 per capita; by comparison, the 2010 census per-capita cost for China was about US$1 and for India was US$0.40.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/2010-united-states-census] Operational costs were $5.4 billion, significantly under the $7 billion budget.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/2010-united-states-census] In December 2010 the Government Accountability Office (GAO) noted that the cost of conducting the census has approximately doubled each decade since 1970.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/2010-united-states-census] In a detailed 2004 report to Congress, the GAO called on the Census Bureau to address cost and design issues, and at that time, had estimated the 2010 census cost to be $11 billion.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/2010-united-states-census] Locke credited the management practices of Census Bureau director Robert Groves, citing in particular the decision to buy additional advertising in locations where responses lagged, which improved the overall response rate.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/2010-united-states-census] The agency also has begun to rely more on questioning neighbors or other reliable third parties when a person could not be immediately reached at home, which reduced the cost of follow-up visits.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/2010-united-states-census] Census data for about 22% of U.S. households that did not reply by mail were based on such outside interviews, Groves said.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/2010-united-states-census] In 2005, Lockheed Martin won a six-year, $500 million contract to capture and standardize data for the census.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/2010-united-states-census] The contract included systems, facilities, and staffing.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/2010-united-states-census] The final value of that contract was in excess of one billion dollars.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/2010-united-states-census] Information technology was about a quarter of the projected $11.3 billion cost of the decennial census.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/2010-united-states-census] The use of high-speed document scanning technology, such as ImageTrac scanners developed by IBML, helped Lockheed Martin complete the project on schedule and under budget.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/2010-united-states-census] Due to the rise in social media and cell-phone usage in the U.S., the Census Bureau used research gathered through a cell-phone study in order to target media and ads to populations that were nonrespondents and promote census participation.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/2010-united-states-census] This study also helped gauge the mindset of those who fail to respond, trying to figure out why.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/2010-united-states-census] This was the first census to use hand-held computing devices with GPS capability, although they were only used for the address canvassing operation.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/2010-united-states-census] Enumerators (information gatherers) that had operational problems with the device understandably made negative reports.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/2010-united-states-census] During the 2009 Senate confirmation hearings for Robert Groves, President Obama's Census Director appointee, there was much mention of contracting problems but very little criticism of the units themselves.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/2010-united-states-census] The Census Bureau chose to conduct the primary operation, Non-Response Follow Up (NRFU), without using the handheld computing devices.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/2010-united-states-census] There was a penalty of $100 for not completing some or all of the 2010 U.S.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/2010-united-states-census] Census Bureau director Robert Grove, however, wrote "the Census Bureau has rarely prosecuted failure to respond.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/2010-united-states-census] While the rationale for the mandatory nature of the census still applies today, our message for the 2010 Census is about the common good benefits of participation".
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/2010-united-states-census] The fine for non-participation is much lower than that for reporting false information.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/2010-united-states-census] The Association of Community Organizations for Reform Now (ACORN) was given a contract to help publicize the importance of the census count and to encourage individuals to fill out their forms.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/2010-united-states-census] In September 2009, after controversial undercover videos showing four ACORN staffers giving tax advice to a man and a woman posing as a prostitute, the bureau canceled ACORN's contract.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/2010-united-states-census] Various American celebrities, including Demi Lovato and Eva Longoria, were used in public service announcements targeting younger people to fill out census forms.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/2010-united-states-census] Wilmer Valderrama and Rosario Dawson have helped spread census awareness among young Hispanics, a historically low participating ethnicity in the U.S. census.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/2010-united-states-census] Rapper Ludacris also participated in efforts to spread awareness of the 2010 census.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/2010-united-states-census] The Census Bureau hired about 635,000 people to find those U.S. residents who had not returned their forms by mail; as of May 28, 2010, 113 census workers had been victims of crime while conducting the census.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/2010-united-states-census] Some political conservatives and libertarians questioned the validity of the questions and even encouraged people to refuse to answer questions for privacy and constitutional reasons.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/2010-united-states-census] As a result, the Census Bureau undertook an unprecedented advertising campaign targeted at encouraging white political conservatives to fill out their forms, in the hope of avoiding an undercount of this group.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/2010-united-states-census] The 2010 U.S. census was the primary sponsor at NASCAR races in Atlanta, Bristol, and Martinsville, and sponsored the No.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/2010-united-states-census] 16 Ford Fusion driven by Greg Biffle for part of the season, because of a marketing survey that indicated most NASCAR fans lean politically conservative.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/2010-united-states-census] It also ran an advertisement during the 2010 Super Bowl, and hired singer Marie Osmond, who is thought to have many conservative fans, to publicize the census.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/2010-united-states-census] The results of the 2010 census determined the number of seats that each state received in the United States House of Representatives starting with the 2012 elections.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/2010-united-states-census] Consequently, this affected the number of votes each state had in the Electoral College for the 2012 presidential election.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/2010-united-states-census] Because of population changes, eighteen states had changes in their number of seats.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/2010-united-states-census] Eight states gained at least one seat, and ten states lost at least one seat.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/2010-united-states-census] The final result involved 12 seats being switched.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/2010-united-states-census] Some objected to the counting of persons who are in the United States illegally.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/2010-united-states-census] Senators David Vitter (R-LA) and Bob Bennett (R-UT) tried unsuccessfully to add questions on immigration status to the census form.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/2010-united-states-census] Organizations such as the Prison Policy Initiative argued that the census counts of incarcerated men and women as residents of prisons, rather than of their pre-incarceration addresses, skewed political clout and resulted in misleading demographic and population data.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/2010-united-states-census] Many residents of prisons counted on the 2010 census were those who identify as Black and Hispanic.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/2010-united-states-census] This could lead to the loss of resources for underserved minority communities.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/2010-united-states-census] The term "Negro" was used in the questionnaire as one of the options for African Americans (Question 9.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/2010-united-states-census] Black, African Am., or Negro) as a choice to describe one's race.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/2010-united-states-census] Census Bureau spokesman Jack Martin explained that "many older African-Americans identified themselves that way, and many still do.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/2010-united-states-census] Those who identify themselves as Negroes need to be included." The word was also used in the 2000 census, with over 56,000 people identifying themselves as "Negro".
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/2010-united-states-census] In response to complaints over the word's inclusion on the 2010 census, the Census Bureau announced in 2013 that it would stop using "Negro" going forward, with the 2014 American Community Survey census form being the first without the word.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/2010-united-states-census] The 2010 census contained ten questions about age, gender, ethnicity, home ownership, and household relationships.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/2010-united-states-census] Six of the ten questions were to be answered for each individual in the household.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/2010-united-states-census] Federal law has provisions for fining those who refuse to complete the census form.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/2010-united-states-census] Detroit Mayor Dave Bing held a press conference on March 22, 2011, to announce that the city would challenge its census results.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/2010-united-states-census] The challenge, being led by the city's planning department, cited an inconsistency as an example showing a downtown census tract which lost only 60 housing units, but 1,400 people, implying that a downtown jail or dormitory was missed in canvassing.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/2010-united-states-census] NYC Mayor Michael Bloomberg held a conference on March 27, 2011, to announce that the city would also challenge his city's census results, specifically the apparent undercounting in the boroughs of Queens and Brooklyn.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/2010-united-states-census] Bloomberg said that the numbers for Queens and Brooklyn, the two most populous boroughs, are implausible.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/2010-united-states-census] According to the census, they grew by only 0.1% and 1.6%, respectively, while the other boroughs grew by between 3% and 5%.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/2010-united-states-census] He also stated that the census showed improbably high numbers of vacant housing in vital neighborhoods such as Jackson Heights, Queens.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/2010-united-states-census] The District of Columbia announced in August 2011 that it would also challenge its census results.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/2010-united-states-census] The Mayor's Office claimed that the detailed information provided for 549 census blocks is "nonsensical", listing examples of census data that show housing units located in the middle of a street that does not actually exist.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/2010-united-states-census] However, officials do not believe the city's total population will drastically change as a result of the challenge.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/2010-united-states-census] The state with the highest percentage rate of growth was Nevada, while the state with the largest population increase was Texas.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/2010-united-states-census] Michigan, the 8th largest by population, was the only state to lose population (although Puerto Rico, a U.S. territory, lost population as well), and the District of Columbia saw its first gain since the 1950s.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/2010-united-states-census] The resident populations listed below do not include people living overseas.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/2010-united-states-census] For Congressional apportionment, the sum of a state's resident population and its population of military personnel and federal contractors living overseas (but not other citizens overseas, such as missionaries or expatriate workers) is used.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/2010-united-states-census] These are core metropolitan rankings versus combined statistical areas.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/2010-united-states-census] For full list with current data, go to metropolitan statistics.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/401k-plans] In the United States, a **401(k)** plan is an employer-sponsored, defined-contribution, personal pension (savings) account, as defined in subsection 401(k) of the U.S.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/401k-plans] Periodic employee contributions come directly out of their paychecks, and may be matched by the employer.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/401k-plans] This pre-tax option is what makes traditional 401(k) plans attractive to employees, and many employers offer this option to their full-time workers.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/401k-plans] 401(k) payable is a general ledger account that contains the amount of 401(k) plan pension payments that an employer has an obligation to remit to a pension plan administrator.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/401k-plans] This account is classified as a payroll liability, since the amount owed should be paid within one year.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/401k-plans] There are two types of 401(k) plans: traditional and Roth.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/401k-plans] For traditional accounts, contributions may be deducted from taxable income and withdrawals are added to taxable income.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/401k-plans] For Roth accounts, contributions and withdrawals have no impact on income tax due to contributions originating from post-tax income.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/401k-plans] There are limits to contributions, rules governing withdrawals, and possible penalties.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/401k-plans] Before 1974, some U.S. employers had been giving their staff the option of receiving cash in lieu of an employer-paid contribution to their tax-qualified retirement plan accounts.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/401k-plans] Congress banned new plans of this type in 1974, pending further study.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/401k-plans] After that study was completed, Congress reauthorized such plans, provided they satisfied certain special requirements.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/401k-plans] Congress did this by enacting Internal Revenue Code Section 401(k) as part of the Revenue Act.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/401k-plans] The first implementation of the 401(k) plan was in 1978, about three weeks after Section 401(k) was enacted, before the Revenue Act of 1978 even went into effect.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/401k-plans] Ethan Lipsig, of the outside law firm for Hughes Aircraft Company, sent a letter to Hughes Aircraft outlining how it could convert its after-tax savings plan into a 401(k) plan.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/401k-plans] Ted Benna was among the first to establish a 401(k) plan, creating it at his own employer, the Johnson Companies (today doing business as Johnson Kendall & Johnson).
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/401k-plans] Benna was trying to reduce the taxes due on a deferred-compensation bonus plan for bank executives, at a time when the top marginal income tax rate was 70%.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/401k-plans] Employees could contribute 25% of their salaries, up to $30,000 per year, to their employer's 401(k) plan.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/401k-plans] There are two main types corresponding to the same distinction in an Individual Retirement Account (IRA); variously referred to as traditional vs.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/401k-plans] Roth, or tax deferred vs. tax exempt, or EET vs.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/401k-plans] The tax-saving benefits from Traditional accounts (as measured by the difference in outcomes vs a normally taxed account) come from two factors.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/401k-plans] The first benefit equals the withdrawal amount multiplied by the difference in tax rates between contribution and withdrawal.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/401k-plans] Effective tax rates are used to incorporate the impact of contributions and draws on the saver's qualification for benefits from other income-tested programs.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/401k-plans] Second, everyone always receives the same benefit as from a Roth account - permanently tax-free profits on after-tax savings.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/401k-plans] The conceptual understanding is that the contribution's tax reduction is the government investing its money alongside the saver's, for him to invest as he likes.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/401k-plans] The government's share of the account at withdrawal (its funding plus the tax-free profits earned by it), fully funds the account's withdrawal tax calculated at the contribution's tax rate.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/401k-plans] So the contribution's tax reduction is never a benefit, and profits are never taxed.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/401k-plans] The withdrawal tax is conceptually an allocation of principal between owners, not a 'tax', and there is no benefit 'from deferral'.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/401k-plans] For pre-tax contributions, the employee still pays the total 7.65% payroll taxes (social security and medicare).
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/401k-plans] If the employee made after-tax contributions to the 401(k) account, these amounts are commingled with the pre-tax funds and simply add to the 401(k) basis.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/401k-plans] When distributions are made, the taxable portion of the distribution will be calculated as the ratio of the after-tax contributions to the total 401(k) basis.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/401k-plans] The remainder of the distribution is tax-free and not included in gross income for the year.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/401k-plans] Beginning in the 2006 tax year, employees have been allowed to designate contributions as a Roth 401(k) deferral.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/401k-plans] Similar to the provisions of a Roth IRA, these contributions are made on an after-tax basis.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/401k-plans] For accumulated after-tax contributions and earnings in a designated Roth account (Roth 401(k)), "qualified distributions" can be made tax-free.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/401k-plans] To qualify, distributions must be made more than 5 years after the first designated Roth contributions *and* not before the year in which the account owner turns age 59+1⁄2, unless an exception applies as detailed in IRS code section 72(t).
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/401k-plans] In the case of designated Roth contributions, the contributions being made on an after-tax basis means that the taxable income in the year of contribution is not decreased as it is with pre-tax contributions.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/401k-plans] Roth contributions are irrevocable and cannot be converted to pre-tax contributions at a later date.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/401k-plans] Unlike the Roth IRA, there is no upper-income limit capping eligibility for Roth 401(k) contributions.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/401k-plans] Individuals who find themselves disqualified from a Roth IRA may contribute to their Roth 401(k).
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/401k-plans] Individuals who qualify for both can contribute the maximum statutory amounts into either or a combination of the two plans (including both catch-up contributions if applicable).
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/401k-plans] Aggregate statutory annual limits set by the IRS will apply.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/401k-plans] Generally, a 401(k) participant may begin to withdraw money from his or her plan after reaching the age of 59+1⁄2 without penalty.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/401k-plans] The Internal Revenue Code imposes severe restrictions on withdrawals of tax-deferred or Roth contributions while a person remains in service with the company and is under the age of 59+1⁄2.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/401k-plans] Amounts withdrawn are subject to ordinary income taxes to the participant.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/401k-plans] The Internal Revenue Code generally defines a hardship as any of the following.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/401k-plans] Some employers may disallow one, several, or all of the previous hardship causes.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/401k-plans] To maintain the tax advantage for income deferred into a 401(k), the law stipulates the restriction that unless an exception applies, money must be kept in the plan or an equivalent tax deferred plan until the employee reaches 59+1⁄2 years of age.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/401k-plans] Money that is withdrawn prior to the age of 59+1⁄2 typically incurs a 10% penalty tax unless a further exception applies.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/401k-plans] This penalty is on top of the "ordinary income" tax that has to be paid on such a withdrawal.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/401k-plans] This does not apply to the similar 457 plan.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/401k-plans] As a response to the COVID-19 pandemic, the CARES Act allowed people to withdraw funds before the age of 59+1⁄2 up to $100,000 without the 10% penalty due for 2020.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/401k-plans] Many plans also allow participants to take loans from their 401(k).
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/401k-plans] The "interest" on the loan is paid not to the financial institution, but is instead paid into the 401(k) plan itself, essentially becoming additional after-tax contributions to the 401(k).
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/401k-plans] The movement of the principal portion of the loan is tax-neutral as long as it is properly paid back.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/401k-plans] However, the interest portion of the loan repayments are made with after-tax funds but do not increase the after-tax basis in the 401(k).
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/401k-plans] Therefore, upon distribution/conversion of those funds, the owner will have to pay taxes on (only) the interest funds a second time.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/401k-plans] The loan principal is not taxable income nor subject to the 10% penalty as long as it is paid back in accordance with section 72(p) of the Internal Revenue Code.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/401k-plans] Employers, of course, have the option to make their plan's loan provisions more restrictive.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/401k-plans] When an employee does not make payments in accordance with the plan or IRS regulations, the outstanding loan balance will be declared in "default".
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/401k-plans] A defaulted loan, and possibly accrued interest on the loan balance, becomes a taxable distribution to the employee in the year of default with all the same tax penalties and implications of a withdrawal.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/401k-plans] Account owners must begin making distributions from their accounts by April 1 of the calendar year after turning age 70+1⁄2 (72 for individuals who turn age 70+1⁄2 after December 31, 2019) or April 1 of the calendar year after retiring, whichever is later.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/401k-plans] The amount of distributions is based on life expectancy according to the relevant factors from the appropriate IRS tables.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/401k-plans] The required minimum distribution is *not* required for a particular calendar year if the account owner is employed by the employer during the entire calendar year *and* the account owner does not own more than 5% of the employer's business at any point during the calendar year.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/401k-plans] Required minimum distributions apply to both traditional contributions and Roth contributions to a 401(k) plan.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/401k-plans] A person who is required to make a required minimum distribution, but does not do so, is subject to a penalty of 50% of the amount that should have been distributed.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/401k-plans] In response to the United States economic crisis of 2007–2009, Congress suspended the RMD requirement for 2009.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/401k-plans] It was suspended again in 2020 due to the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/401k-plans] A 401(k) plan may have a provision in its plan documents to close the account of former employees who have low account balances.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/401k-plans] Almost 90% of 401(k) plans have such a provision.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/401k-plans] As of March 2005, a 401(k) plan may require the closing of a former employee's account only if the former employee's account has less than $1,000 of vested assets.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/401k-plans] Rollovers between eligible retirement plans are accomplished in one of two ways: by a distribution to the participant and a subsequent rollover to another plan or by a direct rollover from plan to plan.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/401k-plans] Rollovers after a distribution to the participant must generally be accomplished within 60 days of the distribution.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/401k-plans] If the 60-day limit is not met, the rollover will be disallowed and the distribution will be taxed as ordinary income and the 10% penalty will apply, if applicable.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/401k-plans] The same rules and restrictions apply to rollovers from plans to IRAs.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/401k-plans] A direct rollover from an eligible retirement plan to another eligible retirement plan is not taxable, regardless of the age of the participant.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/401k-plans] In 2013, the IRS began allowing conversions of existing Traditional 401(k) contributions to Roth 401(k).
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/401k-plans] In order to do so, an employee's company plan must offer both a Traditional and Roth option and explicitly permit such a conversion.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/401k-plans] There is a maximum limit on the total yearly *employee* pre-tax or Roth salary deferral into the plan.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/401k-plans] For future years, the limit may be indexed for inflation, increasing in increments of $500.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/401k-plans] Employees who are at least 50 years old at any time during the year are now allowed additional pre-tax "catch up" contributions of up to $6,000 for 2015–2019, and $6,500 for 2020–2021.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/401k-plans] The limit for future "catch up" contributions may also be adjusted for inflation in increments of $500.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/401k-plans] In eligible plans, employees can elect to contribute on a pre-tax basis or as a Roth 401(k) contribution, or a combination of the two, but the total of those two contributions amounts must not exceed the contribution limit in a single calendar year.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/401k-plans] This limit does not apply to post-tax non-Roth elections.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/401k-plans] If the employee contributes more than the maximum pre-tax/Roth limit to 401(k) accounts in a given year, the excess, as well as the deemed earnings for those contributions, must be withdrawn or corrected by April 15 of the following year.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/401k-plans] This violation most commonly occurs when a person switches employers mid-year and the latest employer does not know to enforce the contribution limits on behalf of their employee.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/401k-plans] Plans which are set up under section 401(k) can also have employer contributions that cannot exceed other regulatory limits.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/401k-plans] Employer matching contributions can be made on behalf of designated Roth contributions, but the employer match must be made on a pre-tax basis.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/401k-plans] Some plans also have a profit-sharing provision where employers make additional contributions to the account and may or may not require matching contributions by the employee.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/401k-plans] These additional contributions may or may not require a matching employee contribution to earn them.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/401k-plans] As with the matching funds, these contributions are also made on a pre-tax basis.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/401k-plans] There is also a maximum 401(k) contribution limit that applies to all employee and employer 401(k) contributions in a calendar year.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/401k-plans] This limit is the section 415 limit, which is the lesser of 100% of the employee's total pre-tax compensation or $56,000 for 2019, or $57,000 in 2020.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/401k-plans] For employees over 50, the catch-up contribution limit is also added to the section 415 limit.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/401k-plans] Governmental employers in the United States (that is, federal, state, county, and city governments) are currently barred from offering 401(k) retirement plans unless the retirement plan was established before May 1986.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/401k-plans] Governmental organizations may set up a section 457(b) retirement plan instead.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/401k-plans] For a corporation, or an LLC taxed as a corporation, contributions must be made by the end of a calendar year.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/401k-plans] For a sole proprietorship, partnership, or an LLC taxed as a sole proprietorship, the deadline for depositing contributions is generally the personal tax filing deadline (April 15, or September 15 if an extension was filed).
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/401k-plans] To help ensure that companies extend their 401(k) plans to low-paid employees, an IRS rule limits the maximum deferral by the company's highly compensated employees (HCEs) based on the average deferral by the company's non-highly compensated employees (NHCEs).
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/401k-plans] If the less compensated employees save more for retirement, then the HCEs are allowed to save more for retirement.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/401k-plans] This provision is enforced via "non-discrimination testing".
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/401k-plans] Non-discrimination testing takes the deferral rates of HCEs and compares them to NHCEs.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/401k-plans] In 2008, an HCE was defined as an employee with compensation greater than $100,000 in 2007, or as an employee that owned more than 5% of the business at any time during the year or the preceding year.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/401k-plans] In addition to the $100,000 limit for determining HCEs, employers can elect to limit the top-paid group of employees to the top 20% of employees ranked by compensation.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/401k-plans] That is, for plans with the first day of the plan-year in the 2007 calendar year, HCEs are employees who earned more than $100,000 in gross compensation (also known as 'Medicare wages') in the prior year.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/401k-plans] For example, most testing done in 2009 was for the 2008 plan-year, which compared 2007 plan-year gross compensation to the $100,000 threshold in order to determine who was an HCE and who was an NHCE.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/401k-plans] The actual deferral percentage (ADP) of all HCEs as a group cannot be two percentage points greater than all NHCEs as a group.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/401k-plans] When a plan fails the ADP test, it essentially has two options to come into compliance.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/401k-plans] A return of excess can be given to the HCEs to lower the HCE ADP to a passing level, or it can process a "qualified non-elective contribution" (QNEC) to some or all of the NHCEs in order to raise the NHCE ADP to a passing level.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/401k-plans] A return of excess requires the plan to send a taxable distribution to the HCEs (or reclassify regular contributions as catch-up contributions subject to the annual catch-up limit for those HCEs over 50) by March 15 of the year following the failed test.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/401k-plans] The annual contribution percentage (ACP) test is similarly performed but also includes employer matching and employee after-tax contributions.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/401k-plans] ACPs do not use the simple 2% threshold, and include other provisions which can allow the plan to "shift" excess passing rates from the ADP over to the ACP.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/401k-plans] A failed ACP test is likewise addressed through return of excess, or a QNEC or qualified match (QMAC).
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/401k-plans] There are a number of "safe harbor" provisions that can allow a company to be exempted from the ADP test.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/401k-plans] This includes making a "safe harbor" employer contribution to employees' accounts.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/401k-plans] Safe harbor contributions can take the form of a match (generally totaling 4% of pay) or a non-elective profit sharing (totaling 3% of pay).
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/401k-plans] Safe harbor 401(k) contributions must be 100% vested at all times with immediate eligibility for employees.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/401k-plans] There are other administrative requirements within the safe harbor, such as requiring the employer to notify all eligible employees of the opportunity to participate in the plan, and restricting the employer from suspending participants for any reason other than due to a hardship withdrawal.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/401k-plans] Employers are allowed to automatically enroll their employees in 401(k) plans, requiring employees to actively opt out if they do not want to participate (traditionally, 401(k)s required employees to opt in).
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/401k-plans] Companies offering such automatic 401(k)s must choose a default investment fund and saving rate.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/401k-plans] Employees who are enrolled automatically will become investors in the default fund at the default rate, although they may select different funds and rates if they choose, or even opt out completely.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/401k-plans] Automatic 401(k)s are designed to encourage high participation rates among employees.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/401k-plans] Therefore, employers can attempt to enroll non-participants as often as once per year, requiring those non-participants to opt out each time if they do not want to participate.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/401k-plans] Employers can also choose to escalate participants' default contribution rate, encouraging them to save more.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/401k-plans] The Pension Protection Act of 2006 made automatic enrollment a safer option for employers.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/401k-plans] Prior to the Pension Protection Act, employers were held responsible for investment losses as a result of such automatic enrollments.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/401k-plans] The Pension Protection Act established a safe harbor for employers in the form of a "Qualified Default Investment Alternative", an investment plan that, if chosen by the employer as the default plan for automatically enrolled participants, relieves the employer of financial liability.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/401k-plans] Under Department of Labor regulations, three main types of investments qualify as QDIAs: lifecycle funds, balanced funds, and managed accounts.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/401k-plans] QDIAs provide sponsors with fiduciary relief similar to the relief that applies when participants affirmatively elect their investments.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/401k-plans] 401(k) plans charge fees for administrative services, record-keeping services, investment management services, and sometimes outside consulting services.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/401k-plans] They can be charged to the employer, the plan participants or to the plan itself and the fees can be allocated on a per participant basis, per plan, or as a percentage of the plan's assets.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/401k-plans] For 2011, the average total administrative and management fees on a 401(k) plan was 0.78 percent or approximately $250 per participant.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/401k-plans] However small businesses can suffer especially higher plan fees.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/401k-plans] The United States Supreme Court ruled, in 2015, that plan administrators could be sued for excessive plan fees and expenses, in Tibble v.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/401k-plans] In the Tibble case, the Supreme Court took strong issue with a large company placing plan investments in "retail" mutual fund shares as opposed to "institutional" class shares.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/401k-plans] The IRS monitors defined contribution plans such as 401(k)s to determine if they are top-heavy, or weighted too heavily in providing benefits to key employees.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/401k-plans] If the plans are too top-heavy, the company must remedy this by allocating funds to the other employees' (known as non-key employees) benefit plans.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/401k-plans] The Economic Growth and Tax Relief Reconciliation Act of 2001 (EGTRRA) made 401(k) plans more beneficial to the self-employed.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/401k-plans] The two key changes enacted related to the allowable "Employer" deductible contribution, and the "Individual" IRC-415 contribution limit.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/401k-plans] Prior to EGTRRA, the maximum tax-deductible contribution to a 401(k) plan was 15% of eligible pay (reduced by the amount of salary deferrals).
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/401k-plans] Without EGTRRA, an incorporated business person taking $100,000 in salary would have been limited in Y2004 to a maximum contribution of $15,000.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/401k-plans] EGTRRA raised the deductible limit to 25% of eligible pay without reduction for salary deferrals.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/401k-plans] Therefore, that same businessperson in Y2008 can make an "elective deferral" of $15,500 plus a profit sharing contribution of $25,000 (i.e.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/401k-plans] 25%), and—if this person is over age 50—make a catch-up contribution of $5,000 for a total of $45,500.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/401k-plans] For those eligible to make "catch-up" contribution, and with salary of $122,000 or higher, the maximum possible total contribution in 2008 would be $51,000.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/401k-plans] To take advantage of these higher contributions, many vendors now offer Solo 401(k) plans or Individual(k) plans, which can be administered as a Self-Directed 401(k), permitting investment in real estate, mortgage notes, tax liens, private companies, and virtually any other investment.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/401k-plans] Notably, an unincorporated business person is subject to slightly different calculation.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/401k-plans] The government mandates calculation of profit sharing contribution as 25% of *net self-employment (Schedule C) income*.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/401k-plans] Thus on $100,000 of self-employment income, the contribution would be 20% of the gross self-employment income, 25% of the net after the contribution of $20,000.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/401k-plans] ROBS is an arrangement in which prospective business owners use their 401(k) retirement funds to pay for new business start-up costs.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/401k-plans] ROBS is an acronym from the United States Internal Revenue Service for the IRS ROBS Rollovers as Business Start-Ups Compliance Project.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/401k-plans] ROBS plans, while not considered an abusive tax avoidance transaction, are questionable because they may solely benefit one individual – the individual who rolls over his or her existing retirement 401(k) withdrawal funds to the ROBS plan in a tax-free transaction.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/401k-plans] The ROBS plan then uses the rollover assets to purchase the stock of the new business.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/401k-plans] A C corporation must be set up in order to roll the 401(k) withdrawal.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/401k-plans] Even though the term "401(k)" is a reference to a specific provision of the U.S.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/401k-plans] Internal Revenue Code section 401, it has become so well known that it has been used elsewhere as a generic term to describe analogous legislation.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/401k-plans] For example, in October 2001, Japan adopted legislation allowing the creation of "Japan-version 401(k)" accounts even though no provision of the relevant Japanese codes is in fact called "section 401(k)".
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/401k-plans] Similar pension schemes exist in other nations as well.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/401k-plans] The term is not used in the UK, where analogous pension arrangements are known as personal pension schemes.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/401k-plans] In Australia, they are known as superannuation funds and plays a much greater role in retirement due to the lack of an equivalent to Social Security.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/401k-plans] In Canada RRSPs (Registered Retirement Savings Plan) play a similar role although they don't have to be employer sponsored and have different contribution limits.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/401k-plans] It is also adopted by most state governments for their employees and also opened for the corporate sector.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/401k-plans] It administers a compulsory contributory Provident Fund Scheme, Pension Scheme, and an Insurance Scheme.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/401k-plans] The schemes cover both Indian and international workers (for countries with which bilateral agreements have been signed; 14 such social security agreements are active).
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/401k-plans] It is one of the largest social security organisations in India in terms of the number of covered beneficiaries and the volume of financial transactions undertaken.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/401k-plans] The EPFO's apex decision-making body is the Central Board of Trustees.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/401k-plans] Nepal and Sri Lanka have similar employees provident fund schemes.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/401k-plans] In Malaysia, The Employees Provident Fund (EPF) was established in 1951 upon the Employees Provident Fund Ordinance 1951.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/401k-plans] The EPF is intended to help employees from the private sector save a fraction of their salary in a lifetime banking scheme, to be used primarily as a retirement fund but also in the event that the employee is temporarily or no longer fit to work.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/401k-plans] As of March 31, 2014, the size of the EPF asset size stood at RM597 billion (US$184 billion), making it the fourth-largest pension fund in Asia and seventh-largest in the world.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/401k-plans] Unlike defined-benefit pensions (regulated by ERISA) or an FDIC-insured savings account at a bank, there is no government guarantee for assets held in 401(k) accounts.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/401k-plans] Investments in stocks can lose value due to market fluctuations.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/401k-plans] Diversification can protect against poor performance in any one stock or industry, but not against a widespread decline like the Great Depression or Great Recession.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/401k-plans] Further diversification into bonds can protect against stock market declines, but generally have smaller earning potential and still carry the risk of bondholder default.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/401k-plans] Earners are generally advised to shift from higher-risk, higher-return assets to lower-risk assets as they near retirement age.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/401k-plans] Money can also be lost if the plan sponsor has financial difficulties, though if a sponsor goes bankrupt, 401(k) account holders have high priority.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/401k-plans] Earners can take sponsor risk into account when deciding whether to leave assets in the plan sponsored by a former employer or roll over the assets to a new employer plan or to an individual retirement account (IRA).
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/401k-plans] Fees charged by 401(k) providers can substantially reduce earnings.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/401k-plans] 401(k) plans are restricted to investments chosen by employers.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/401k-plans] This can prevent earners from risky choices like picking individual stocks, but also from following a favored investment strategy or asset types (such as commodities), or choosing socially responsible investing.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/401k-plans] IRA providers typically offer a far wider selection of investments.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/401k-plans] Conversely, 401(k) plans are sometimes criticized for putting the burden of choosing and updating investments on earners, most of whom are not experts in finance.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/401k-plans] Some earners avoid signing up for 401(k)s because of the perceived complexity.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/401k-plans] Target date funds mitigate this complexity by automatically shifting investments from stocks to bonds based on time to planned retirement date.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/401k-plans] The tax breaks given for money invested in 401(k)s are only available to people who earn enough money to be able to save for retirement, and does nothing to help the lowest-income earners.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/401k-plans] Households in the highest earning group saved enough to receive about 11 times more in retirement income.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/401k-plans] This exacerbates existing income inequality, especially if these larger retirement savings are used for the benefit of children (for example to pay for a better education, or simply as inheritance).
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/401k-plans] Offering 401(k)s is not mandatory, so not all employers do so; this means some workers simply cannot benefit from the tax breaks.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/401k-plans] Benefits consultant Ted Benna, who first realized the favorable treatment this section of the tax code afforded defined-contribution plans, has proposed mandating that employers over a certain size offer 401(k)s.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/401k-plans] In 2024, one group of researchers advocated ending the tax break for the 401(k) on the grounds that it did not increase aggregate retirement savings, and using the $200 billion in additional tax revenue to support the government-funded Social Security program.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/401k-plans] The amount of money available in retirement from defined-contribution plans like 401(k)s varies considerably depending on the amount contributed and performance of investments.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/401k-plans] Reliance on these plans instead of defined-benefit pensions and the small fraction of earnings replaced by government programs like Social Security means many people have an insufficient amount of money for retirement.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/401k-plans] According to US Census data, in 2017, 49% of Americans aged 55 to 66 had "no personal retirement savings".
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/401k-plans] This gap can force people to choose between continuing to work into old age (if they are healthy enough to do so) and living in poverty.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/401k-plans] One bipartisan proposal to address this problem is to open the defined-benefit Thrift Savings Plan to all employees (currently it is only for federal government employees).
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/403b-plans] It has tax treatment similar to a 401(k) plan, especially after the Economic Growth and Tax Relief Reconciliation Act of 2001.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/403b-plans] Both plans also require that distributions start at age 73 (effective on January 1, 2023 per SECURE Act 2.0), known as Required Minimum Distributions (RMDs).
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/403b-plans] Roth 403(b) accounts are exempt from RMDs beginning in 2024, also per SECURE Act 2.0.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/403b-plans] Distributions are typically taxed as ordinary income.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/403b-plans] Employee salary deferrals into a 403(b) plan are made before income tax is paid and allowed to grow tax-deferred until the money is taxed as income when withdrawn from the plan.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/403b-plans] 403(b) plans are also referred to as a **tax-sheltered annuity** (**TSA**) although since 1974 they no longer are restricted to an annuity form and participants can also invest in mutual funds.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/403b-plans] A 403(b) account that is able to invest directly in mutual funds is referred to as a 403(b)(7) account or a **tax-sheltered custodial account** (**TSCA**).
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/403b-plans] The Employee Retirement Income Security Act (ERISA) does not require 403(b) plans to be technically "qualified" plans (i.e., plans governed by U.S.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/403b-plans] Tax Code 401(a)), but 403(b) plans have the same general appearance as qualified plans.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/403b-plans] While the option is available it is not known how prevalent or if any 403(b) plan has been started or amended to be ERISA-qualified.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/403b-plans] This is because the main advantage of ERISA plans for participants has been in the event of bankruptcy of the account holder, but this advantage ceased to exist after the October 2007 Bankruptcy Abuse Prevention and Consumer Protection Act extended bankruptcy protection to 403(b) plans.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/403b-plans] While they are different in some fundamental ways, qualified and unqualified plans appear almost the same to the participant and the options available are very similar.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/403b-plans] The only important differences for the participants are some additional ways that they can withdraw employer money, not salary-deferral money, before the typical 59½ age restriction, but only if the plan is funded with annuities and not mutual funds.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/403b-plans] The federal government wants to eliminate this difference in proposed regulations expected to be finalized in 2007.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/403b-plans] From a plan administration standpoint, 403(b) plans do not have many of the same technical difficulties that 401(k) plans do, such as discrimination testing, especially if the plan is not an ERISA plan.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/403b-plans] If the plan *is* an ERISA plan (the employer makes contributions to employee accounts) there are additional restrictions and administrative issues applicable to those employer contributions, but not if a plan of a government employer which is not subject to discrimination testing.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/403b-plans] Salary-deferral contributions are not subject to discrimination testing.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/403b-plans] 403(b) plans are instead subject to universal availability which, briefly and in general, means all employees must be permitted to make salary-deferral contributions.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/403b-plans] 403(b) plans also have simpler and less costly annual reporting requirements on Internal Revenue Service (IRS) Form 5500, including not having the independent auditor requirement applicable to qualified plans with more than 100 plan participants.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/403b-plans] On December 9, 2008, the IRS gave 403(b) plan sponsors a one-year reprieve for adopting a written plan document.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/403b-plans] While the relief provisions from the IRS give 403(b) sponsors a full year to adopt a written plan document, the plans still must operate in compliance with 403(b) plan requirements.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/403b-plans] If a person has taken a 403(b) plan and their age is less than 59½, then they cannot initiate an early withdrawal unless they can demonstrate a triggering event such as financial hardship, disability, or separation from service.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/403b-plans] In this event, the IRS will also charge a mandatory 10% in federal taxes, and it is additionally taxed as ordinary income.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/403b-plans] Before the passage of the bankruptcy reform act in 2005, a 403(b) that was not an ERISA plan was not accorded protected status as property that could be claimed as exempt by the debtor under the U.S.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/403b-plans] 2001) Judge Spector held that the fixed-income annuity was not such a trust and could be reached by creditors.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/403b-plans] The variable account was held to fall within 541(c)(2) and was thus protected.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/403b-plans] Under the revised bankruptcy laws, 403(b) accounts, IRAs, and other retirement accounts are, in general, protected from creditors in bankruptcy.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/403b-plans] For this reason, having an ERISA anti-alienation clause was protective of pensions before the bankruptcy law revisions, giving those pensions the same protection as a spendthrift trust.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/403b-plans] Some critics argued that this is disparate treatment of similar pension schemes and that more consistent protection was called for.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/403b-plans] The United States Congress took this argument to heart in the 2005 bankruptcy reform.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/403b-plans] Beginning in 2006, 403(b) and 401(k) plans may also include designated Roth contributions, i.e., after-tax contributions, which will allow tax-free withdrawals if certain requirements are met.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/403b-plans] Primarily, the designated Roth contributions have to be in the plan for at least five taxable years and the account holder must be at least 59 years of age.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/403b-plans] A church plan is a retirement plan established and maintained by a tax-exempt church, a convention of churches, or an association of churches for its employees.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/403b-plans] Church plans are not subject to the Employee Retirement Income Security Act of 1974 (ERISA) unless it voluntarily makes an irrevocable election to be subject to ERISA.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/403b-plans] A church plan may be a defined benefit plan, a defined contribution plan, or a deferred compensation plan.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/403b-plans] A church plan that is not subject to ERISA is not required to file an IRS Form 5500, nor is it required to distribute summary annual reports, summary plan descriptions, or summaries of material modifications to plan participants.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/403b-plans] Church plans are generally subject to state law though.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/403b-plans] A defined benefit church plan is not required to pay subject to Pension Benefit Guaranty Corporation plan termination insurance.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/a-aninin] The **Gros Ventre** (US: /ˈɡroʊvɒnt/ *GROH-vont*; French: [ɡʁo vɑ̃tʁ], meaning 'big belly'), also known as the **A'aninin**, **Atsina**, or **White Clay**, are a historically Algonquian-speaking Native American tribe located in northcentral Montana.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/a-aninin] Today, the Gros Ventre people are enrolled in the Fort Belknap Indian Community of the Fort Belknap Reservation of Montana, a federally recognized tribe with 7,000 members, also including the Assiniboine people.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/a-aninin] The name used by the Gros Ventre, *ʔɔʔɔɔ̋ɔ́niinénnɔh* means "White Clay People".
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/a-aninin] It has a variety of transliterations, including *A'aninin*, *Aaniiih*, *Haaninin*, *Aainen*, *Aa'ninena*, and *Aaninena*.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/a-aninin] The French used the term *Gros Ventre*, which was mistakenly interpreted from sign language.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/a-aninin] They were once known as the "Gros Ventres of the Prairies", as the Hidatsa people were similarly called the "Gros Ventres of the Missouri".
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/a-aninin] The Gros Ventres are believed to have lived in the western Great Lakes region 3,000 years ago, where they lived an agrarian lifestyle, cultivating maize.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/a-aninin] With the ancestors of the Arapaho, they formed a single Algonquian-speaking people who lived along the Red River Valley in present-day Minnesota and North Dakota.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/a-aninin] In Ojibwa oral history they are known as the "men of the olden time" that occupied the lands surrounding the head waters of the Mississippi River.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/a-aninin] They were closely associated with the ancestors of the Cheyenne.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/a-aninin] They spoke the now nearly extinct Gros Ventre language (Atsina), a closely related Plains Algonquian language, much like the Arapaho, and is grouped as an Arapahoan language (Arapaho-Atsina).
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/a-aninin] There is evidence that, together with bands of Northern Arapaho, a southern tribal group, the *Staetan*, spoke the Besawunena dialect, which had speakers among the Northern Arapaho as recently as the late 1920s.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/a-aninin] In the early 18th century, the combined tribe came under pressure from the Ojibwe, and started a migration to the upper Missouri River Valley.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/a-aninin] During the migration, the large tribe split into the Arapaho and the Gros Ventre, possibly near Devil's Lake.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/a-aninin] These groups, along with the Cheyenne, were among the last to migrate into Montana, due to pressure from the Ojibwe.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/a-aninin] After they migrated to Montana, the Arapaho moved southwards to the Wyoming and Colorado area.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/a-aninin] The Cheyenne who migrated with the Gros Ventre and Arapaho also migrated onwards.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/a-aninin] The Gros Ventre acquired horses in the mid-18th century.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/a-aninin] The earliest known contact of Gros Ventre with whites was around 1754, between the north and south forks of the Saskatchewan River.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/a-aninin] Exposure to smallpox severely reduced their numbers.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/a-aninin] Around 1793, in response to attacks by well-armed Cree and Assiniboines, large groups of Gros Ventre burned two Hudson's Bay Company trading posts that were providing guns to the Cree and Assiniboine in what is now Saskatchewan.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/a-aninin] In 1832, the Gros Ventre made contact with the German explorer and naturalist, Prince Maximilian.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/a-aninin] Along with the naturalist painter Karl Bodmer, the Europeans painted portraits and recorded their meeting with the Gros Ventre, near the Missouri River in Montana.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/a-aninin] The Gros Ventres joined the Blackfoot Confederacy, after which they moved to north-central Montana and southern Canada.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/a-aninin] In 1855, Isaac Stevens, Territorial Governor of the Washington Territory, signed a treaty (11 Stat.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/a-aninin] 657) to make peace between the United States and the Blackfoot, Flathead and Nez Perce tribes.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/a-aninin] The Gros Ventres signed the treaty as part of the Blackfoot Confederacy, whose territory near the Three Fork area became a common hunting ground for the combined peoples.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/a-aninin] A common hunting ground north of the Missouri River on the Fort Peck Indian Reservation included the Assiniboine and Sioux.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/a-aninin] In 1861, the Gros Ventres left the Blackfoot Confederacy.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/a-aninin] Allying with the Crow, the Gros Ventres fought the Blackfoot but in 1867, they were defeated.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/a-aninin] In 1868, the United States government established a trading post called Fort Browning near the mouth of Peoples Creek on the Milk River.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/a-aninin] This trading post was built for the Gros Ventres and Assiniboines, but because it was on a favorite hunting ground of the Sioux, it was abandoned in 1871.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/a-aninin] The government then built Fort Belknap, which was established on the south side of the Milk River, about one mile southwest of the present town site of Harlem, Montana.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/a-aninin] Fort Belknap was a substation post, with half of the structure being a trading post.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/a-aninin] A block house stood to the left of the stockade gate.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/a-aninin] At the right was a warehouse and an issue building, where the tribe received their rations and annuity goods.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/a-aninin] In 1876, the fort was discontinued and the Gros Ventre and Assiniboine people receiving annuities at the post were instructed to go to the agency at Fort Peck and Wolf Point.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/a-aninin] The Assiniboines readily did so, but the Gros Ventres refused, fearing coming into conflict with the nearby Sioux.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/a-aninin] They chose to forfeit their annuities rather than move to Fort Peck.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/a-aninin] In 1878, the Fort Belknap Agency was re-established, and the Gros Ventres, and remaining Assiniboines were again allowed to receive supplies at Fort Belknap.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/a-aninin] White Eagle, "the last major Chief of the Gros Ventre people", died "at the mouth of the Judith River" on February 9, 1881.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/a-aninin] In 1884, gold was discovered in the Little Rocky Mountains.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/a-aninin] Pressure from miners and mining companies forced the tribes to cede sections of the mountains in 1885.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/a-aninin] Jesuits came to Fort Belknap in 1862 to convert the Gros Ventre people to Roman Catholicism.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/a-aninin] Paul's Mission was established at the foot of the Little Rocky Mountains, near Hays.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/a-aninin] The mission repressed traditional ceremonies and culture Two sacred pipes, The Feathered Pipe and The Flat Pipe, still remain central to the traditional spiritual beliefs of the Gros Ventres.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/a-aninin] In 1888, the Fort Belknap Indian Reservation was established by an act of Congress on May 1, 1888 (Stat., L., XXV, 113).
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/a-aninin] The Blackfoot, Gros Ventre, and Assiniboine tribes under coercion ceded a combined 17,500,000 acres of their joint reservation and were allowed to live on three smaller reservations.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/a-aninin] These are now known as the Blackfoot Confederacy, the Fort Peck Indian Reservation and the Fort Belknap Indian Reservation.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/a-aninin] By 1904, there were only 535 Gros Ventre tribe members remaining.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/a-aninin] The tribe has since revived, with a substantial increase in population.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/a-aninin] In March 2012, 63 American bison from Yellowstone National Park were transferred to prairie on the Fort Peck Indian Reservation, to be released to a 2,100-acre game preserve 25 miles north of Poplar.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/a-aninin] There are numerous other bison herds outside Yellowstone, but the herd transferred is one of the very few not cross-bred with cattle.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/a-aninin] Many celebrated the move, over a century after bison were nearly made extinct by White settlers and the government.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/a-aninin] The Assiniboine and Gros Ventre tribes at the Fort Belknap Indian Reservation also received a portion of the herd.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/a-aninin] The reservation government of Fort Belknap has an elected community council with 4 Gros Ventre members and 4 Assiniboine, for a total of 8 elected members of the council.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/a-aninin] The officers of the council are the President, Vice President, and Secretary-Treasurer, with the Secretary-Treasurer being appointed by the president and confirmed by the council.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/a-aninin] The secretary-treasurer, as the only appointed officer, may not vote on council matters.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/a-aninin] The constitution and bylaws of the Fort Belknap Indian Reservation were ratified on September 25, 1935, and adopted on October 19, 1935.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abenaki] The **Abenaki** (Abenaki: *Wôbanaki*) are an Indigenous people of the Northeastern Woodlands of Canada and the United States.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abenaki] They are an Algonquian-speaking people and part of the Wabanaki Confederacy.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abenaki] The Eastern Abenaki language was predominantly spoken in Maine, while the Western Abenaki language was spoken in Quebec, Vermont, and New Hampshire.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abenaki] While Abenaki peoples share cultural traits, they historically did not have a centralized government.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abenaki] They came together as a post-contact community after their original tribes were decimated by colonization, disease, and warfare.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abenaki] The word *Abenaki* and its syncope, *Abnaki,* are both derived from *Wabanaki*, or *Wôbanakiak,* meaning "People of the Dawn Land" in the Abenaki language.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abenaki] While the two terms are often confused, the Abenaki are one of several tribes in the Wabanaki Confederacy.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abenaki] The Abenaki people also call themselves Alnôbak, meaning "Real People", and by the autonym *Alnanbal,* meaning "men".
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abenaki] Historically, ethnologists have classified the Abenaki by geographic groups: Western Abenaki and Eastern Abenaki.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abenaki] The homeland of the Abenaki, called Ndakinna (Our Land; alternately written as N'dakinna or N'Dakinna), previously extended across most of what is now northern New England, southern Quebec, and the southern Canadian Maritimes.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abenaki] The Eastern Abenaki population was concentrated in portions of New Brunswick and Maine east of New Hampshire's White Mountains.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abenaki] The other major group, the Western Abenaki, lived in the Connecticut River valley in Vermont, New Hampshire, and Massachusetts.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abenaki] The Missiquoi lived along the eastern shore of Lake Champlain.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abenaki] The Pennacook lived along the Merrimack River in southern New Hampshire.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abenaki] The maritime Abenaki lived around the St.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abenaki] Croix and Wolastoq (Saint John River) Valleys near the boundary line between Maine and New Brunswick.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abenaki] English colonial settlement in New England and frequent violence forced many Abenaki to migrate to Quebec.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abenaki] The Abenaki settled in the Sillery region of Quebec between 1676 and 1680, and subsequently, for about twenty years, lived on the banks of the Chaudière River near the falls, before settling in Odanak and Wôlinak in the early eighteenth century.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abenaki] In those days, the Abenaki practiced a subsistence economy based on hunting, fishing, trapping, berry picking and on growing corn, beans, squash, potatoes and tobacco.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abenaki] They also produced baskets, made of ash and sweet grass, for picking wild berries, and boiled maple sap to make syrup.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abenaki] Basket weaving remains a traditional activity practiced by some tribal members.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abenaki] During the Anglo-French wars, the Abenaki were allies of France, having been displaced from Ndakinna by immigrating English settlers.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abenaki] An anecdote from the period tells the story of a Wolastoqew war chief named Nescambuit (variant spellings include Assacumbuit), who killed more than 140 enemies of King Louis XIV of France and received the rank of knight.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abenaki] Not all Abenaki people fought on the side of the French, however; many remained on their Native lands in the northern colonies.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abenaki] Much of the trapping was done by the people and traded to the English colonists for durable goods.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abenaki] These contributions by Native American Abenaki peoples went largely unreported.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abenaki] Two tribal communities formed in Canada, one once known as Saint-Francois-du-lac near Pierreville (now called Odanak, Abenaki for "coming home"), and the other near Bécancour (now known as Wôlinak) on the south shore of the St.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abenaki] Lawrence River, directly across the river from Trois-Rivières.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abenaki] These two Abenaki reserves continue to grow and develop.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abenaki] Since the year 2000, the total Abenaki population (on and off reserve) has doubled to 2,101 members in 2011.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abenaki] Approximately 400 Abenaki reside on these two reserves, which cover a total area of less than 7 km2 (2.7 sq mi).
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abenaki] The unrecognized majority are off-reserve members, living in various cities and towns across Canada and the United States.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abenaki] There are about 3,200 Abenaki living in Vermont and New Hampshire, without reservations, chiefly around Lake Champlain.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abenaki] The remaining Abenaki people live in multi-racial towns and cities across Canada and the US, mainly in Ontario, Quebec, New Brunswick, and northern New England.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abenaki] The Abenaki language is closely related to the Panawahpskek (Penobscot) language.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abenaki] Other neighboring Wabanaki tribes, the Pestomuhkati (Passamaquoddy), Wolastoqiyik (Maliseet), and Mi'kmaq, and other Eastern Algonquian languages share many linguistic similarities.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abenaki] It has come close to extinction as a spoken language.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abenaki] Tribal members are working to revive the Abenaki language at Odanak (means "in the village"), a First Nations Abenaki reserve near Pierreville, Quebec, and throughout New Hampshire, Vermont, and New York state.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abenaki] The language is polysynthetic, meaning that a phrase or an entire sentence is expressed by a single word.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abenaki] For example, the word for "white man" *awanoch* is a combination of the words *awani* meaning "who" and *uji* meaning "from".
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abenaki] There is archaeological evidence of Indigenous people in what is today New Hampshire for at least 12,000 years.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abenaki] In *Reflections in Bullough's Pond*, historian Diana Muir argues that the Abenakis' neighbors, pre-contact Iroquois, were an imperialist, expansionist culture whose cultivation of the corn/beans/squash agricultural complex enabled them to support a large population.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abenaki] They made war primarily against neighboring Algonquian peoples, including the Abenaki.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abenaki] Muir uses archaeological data to argue that the Iroquois expansion onto Algonquian lands was checked by the Algonquian adoption of agriculture.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abenaki] This enabled them to support their own populations large enough to have sufficient warriors to defend against the threat of Iroquois conquest.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abenaki] In 1614, Thomas Hunt captured 24 Abenaki people, including Squanto (Tisquantum) and took them to Spain, where they were sold into slavery.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abenaki] During the European colonization of North America, the land occupied by the Abenaki was in the area between the new colonies of England in Massachusetts and the French in Quebec.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abenaki] Since no party agreed to territorial boundaries, there was regular conflict among them.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abenaki] The Abenaki were traditionally allied with the French; during the reign of Louis XIV, Chief Assacumbuit was designated a member of the French nobility for his service.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abenaki] Around 1669, the Abenaki started to emigrate to Quebec due to conflicts with English colonists and epidemics of new infectious diseases.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abenaki] The governor of New France allocated two seigneuries (large self-administered areas similar to feudal fiefs).
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abenaki] The first, of what was later to become Indian reserves, was on the Saint Francis River and is now known as the Odanak Indian Reserve; the second was founded near Bécancour and is called the Wôlinak Indian Reserve.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abenaki] When the Wampanoag under King Philip (Metacomet) fought the English colonists in New England in 1675 in King Philip's War, the Abenaki joined the Wampanoag.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abenaki] For three years they fought along the Maine frontier in the First Abenaki War.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abenaki] The Abenaki pushed back the line of white settlement through devastating raids on scattered farmhouses and small villages.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abenaki] The war was settled by a peace treaty in 1678, with the Wampanoag more than decimated and many Native survivors having been sold into slavery in Bermuda.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abenaki] During Queen Anne's War in 1702, the Abenaki were allied with the French; they raided numerous English colonial settlements in Maine, from Wells to Casco, killing about 300 settlers over ten years.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abenaki] They also occasionally raided into Massachusetts, for instance in Groton and Deerfield in 1704.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abenaki] Some captives were adopted into the Mohawk and Abenaki tribes; older captives were generally ransomed, and the colonies carried on a brisk trade.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abenaki] The Third Abenaki War (1722–25), called the Dummer's War or Father Rale's War, erupted when the French Jesuit missionary Sébastien Rale (or Rasles, ~1657?-1724) encouraged the Abenaki to halt the spread of Yankee settlements.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abenaki] When the Massachusetts militia tried to seize Rale, the Abenaki raided the settlements at Brunswick, Arrowsick, and Merry-Meeting Bay.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abenaki] The Massachusetts government then declared war and bloody battles were fought at Norridgewock (1724), where Rale was killed, and at a daylong battle at the Indian village near present-day Fryeburg, Maine, on the upper Saco River (1725).
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abenaki] Peace conferences at Boston and Casco Bay brought an end to the war.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abenaki] After Rale died, the Abenaki moved to a settlement on the St.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abenaki] Francois continued to raid British settlements in their former homelands along the New England frontier during Father Le Loutre's War (see Northeast Coast campaign (1750)) and the French and Indian War.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abenaki] The development of tourism projects has allowed the Canadian Abenaki to develop a modern economy, while preserving their culture and traditions.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abenaki] For example, since 1960, the Odanak Historical Society has managed the first and one of the largest aboriginal museums in Quebec, a few miles from the Quebec-Montreal axis.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abenaki] Over 5,000 people visit the Abenaki Museum annually.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abenaki] Several Abenaki companies include: in Wôlinak, General Fiberglass Engineering employs a dozen Natives, with annual sales exceeding C$3 million.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abenaki] Odanak is now active in transportation and distribution.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abenaki] Notable Abenaki from this area include the documentary filmmaker Alanis Obomsawin (National Film Board of Canada).
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abenaki] The Penobscot Nation, Passamaquoddy Tribe, and Houlton Band of Maliseet Indians are federally recognized as Native American tribes in the United States.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abenaki] Nulhegan Band of the Coosuk Abenaki Nation, Koasek Abenaki Tribe, Elnu Abenaki Tribe, and the Missisquoi Abenaki Tribe are, as of 2011, have all been state-recognized by Vermont.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abenaki] The Missisquoi Abenaki applied for federal recognition as an Indian tribe in the 1980s but failed to meet four of the seven criteria.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abenaki] The Bureau of Indian Affairs found that less than 1 percent of the Missisquoi's 1,171 members could show descent from an Abenaki ancestor.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abenaki] State recognition allows applicants to seek certain scholarship funds reserved for American Indians and to for members to market artwork as American Indian or Native American–made under the Indian Arts and Crafts Act of 1990.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abenaki] In 2002, the State of Vermont reported that the Abenaki people have not had a "continuous presence" in the state and had migrated north to Quebec by the end of the 17th century.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abenaki] Facing annihilation, many Abenaki had begun emigrating to Canada, then under French control, around 1669.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abenaki] The Abenaki Nation, based in Quebec, claim that those self-identifying as Abenaki in Vermont are settlers making false claims to Indigenous ancestry.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abenaki] While the Odanak and Wolinak Abenaki First Nations in Quebec initially believed claims from residents of Vermont who said they were Abenaki, the Odanak reversed their position in 2003, calling on the groups in Vermont to provide them with genealogical evidence of Indigenous ancestry.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abenaki] Scholars have not been able to find credible evidence of the Vermont Abenaki's claims of Indigenous ancestry.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abenaki] Anthropological research from the first half of the 20th century indicates that no Abenaki community actively existed in Vermont during that time period.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abenaki] Researcher Darryl Leroux characterizes the Vermont Abenaki's claims of Abenaki ancestry as "race-shifting", arguing that genealogical and archival evidence shows that most members of the state-recognized tribes are descended from white French Canadians.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abenaki] Leroux found that only 2.2 percent of the Missisquoi Abenaki membership has Abenaki ancestry, with the rest of the organization's root ancestors being primarily French Canadian and migrating to Vermont in the mid-19th century.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abenaki] The Abenaki Nation of Missisquoi's shifting claims about its root ancestors as well as loose membership criteria are consistent with race-shifting patterns.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abenaki] Leroux's research prompted renewed calls by the Abenaki First Nations to reassess Vermont's state recognition process.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abenaki] In 2025, leaders of the Quebec-based Odanak and Wôlinak communities released a genealogical report they had commissioned into the origins of prominent Vermont-recognized Abenaki leaders.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abenaki] All subjects of the report were found to have at least 96.9 percent European ancestry, although "one or two distant Indigenous ancestors".
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abenaki] Odanak representative Jacques Watso accused the Vermont groups of falsifying their ancestry and allowing "illegitimate groups to obtain official recognition and rights that rightfully belong to the true Abenaki people".
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abenaki] In response, the Vermont leaders issued a joint statement describing the report as "malicious propaganda" and "junk science, compiled with bias and full of factual and interpretative errors".
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abenaki] New Hampshire does not recognize any Abenaki tribes.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abenaki] It has no federally recognized tribes or state-recognized tribes; however, it established the New Hampshire Commission on Native American Affairs in 2010.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abenaki] The various Cowasuck, Abenaki, and other Native and heritage groups are represented to the commission.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abenaki] In 2021, a bill was introduced to the New Hampshire legislature to allow New Hampshire communities to rename locations in the Abenaki language.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abenaki] There are a dozen variations of the name "Abenaki", such as Abenaquiois, Abakivis, Quabenakionek, Wabenakies and others.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abenaki] The Abenaki were described in the *Jesuit Relations* as not cannibals, and as docile, ingenious, temperate in the use of liquor, and not profane.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abenaki] Abenaki lifeways were similar to those of Algonquian-speaking peoples of southern New England.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abenaki] They cultivated food crops and built villages on or near fertile river floodplains.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abenaki] They also hunted game, fished, and gathered wild plants and fungi.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abenaki] Unlike the Haudenosaunee, the Abenaki were patrilineal.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abenaki] Each man had different hunting territories inherited through his father.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abenaki] Most of the year, Abenaki lived in dispersed bands of extended families.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abenaki] Bands came together during the spring and summer at seasonal villages near rivers, or somewhere along the seacoast for planting and fishing.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abenaki] During the winter, the Abenaki lived in small groups further inland.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abenaki] These villages occasionally had to be fortified, depending on the alliances and enemies of other tribes or of Europeans near the village.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abenaki] Abenaki villages were quite small with an average number of 100 residents.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abenaki] Most Abenaki crafted dome-shaped, bark-covered wigwams for housing, though a few preferred oval-shaped longhouses.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abenaki] During the winter, the Abenaki lined the inside of their conical wigwams with bear and deer skins for warmth.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abenaki] The Abenaki were a farming society that supplemented agriculture with hunting and gathering.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abenaki] The women tended the fields and grew the crops.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abenaki] In their fields, they planted the crops in groups of "sisters".
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abenaki] The three sisters were grown together: the stalk of corn supported the beans, and squash or pumpkins provided ground cover and reduced weeds.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abenaki] The men would hunt bears, deer, fish, and birds.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abenaki] The Abenaki were a patrilineal society, which was common among New England tribes.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abenaki] In this they differed from the six Iroquois tribes to the west in New York, and from many other North American Native tribes who had matrilineal societies.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abenaki] Groups used the consensus method to make important decisions.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abenaki] Storytelling is a major part of Abenaki culture.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abenaki] It is used not only as entertainment but also as a teaching method.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abenaki] The Abenaki view stories as having lives of their own and being aware of how they are used.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abenaki] Stories were used as a means of teaching children behavior.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abenaki] Children were not to be mistreated, and so instead of punishing the child, they would be told a story.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abenaki] One of the stories is of Azban the Raccoon.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abenaki] This is a story about a proud raccoon that challenges a waterfall to a shouting contest.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abenaki] When the waterfall does not respond, Azban dives into the waterfall to try to outshout it; he is swept away because of his pride.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abenaki] This story would be used to show a child the pitfalls of pride.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abenaki] The Abenaki smash the flowers and leaves of *Ranunculus acris* and sniff them for headaches.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abenaki] They consume the fruit of *Vaccinium myrtilloides* as part of their traditional diet.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abenaki] They also use the fruit and the grains of *Viburnum nudum var. cassinoides* for food.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abenaki] They use *Hierochloe odorata* (sweetgrass), *Apocynum* (dogbane), *Betula papyrifera* (paper birch), *Fraxinus americana* (white ash), *Fraxinus nigra* (black ash), *Laportea canadensis* (Canada nettle), a variety of *Salix* species, and *Tilia americana* (basswood, or American linden) var.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abenaki] *Americana* for making baskets, canoes, snowshoes, and whistles.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abenaki] They use *Hierochloe odorata* and willow to make containers, *Betula papyrifera* to create containers, moose calls and other utilitarian pieces, and the bark of *Cornus sericea* (red osier dogwood) ssp. sericea for smoking.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abenaki] *latifolia*, *Vaccinium angustifolium*, and *Zea mays* as a tea, soup, jelly, sweetener, condiment, snack, or meal.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abenaki] The Abenaki use the gum of balsam fir trees for slight itches and as an antiseptic ointment.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abenaki] They stuff the leaves, needles and wood into pillows as a panacea.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abenaki] Before the Abenaki, except the Pennacook and Mi'kmaq, had contact with the European world, their population may have numbered as many as 40,000.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abenaki] Around 20,000 would have been Eastern Abenaki, another 10,000 would have been Western Abenaki, and the last 10,000 would have been Maritime Abenaki.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abenaki] Early contact with European fishermen resulted in two major epidemics that affected Abenaki during the 16th century.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abenaki] The first epidemic was an unknown sickness occurring sometime between 1564 and 1570, and the second one was typhus in 1586.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abenaki] Multiple epidemics arrived a decade prior to the English colonization of Massachusetts in 1620, when three separate sicknesses swept across New England and the Canadian Maritimes.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abenaki] Maine was hit very hard during the year of 1617, with a fatality rate of 75 per, and the population of the Eastern Abenaki fell to about 5,000.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abenaki] The more isolated Western Abenaki suffered fewer fatalities, losing about half of their original population of 10,000.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abenaki] The new diseases continued to strike in epidemics, starting with smallpox in 1631, 1633, and 1639.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abenaki] Seven years later, an unknown epidemic struck, with influenza passing through the following year.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abenaki] Smallpox affected the Abenaki again in 1649, and diphtheria came through 10 years later.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abenaki] Smallpox struck in 1670, and influenza in 1675.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abenaki] The Abenaki population continued to decline, but in 1676, they took in thousands of refugees from many southern New England tribes displaced by settlement and King Philip's War.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abenaki] Because of this, descendants of nearly every southern New England Algonquian tribe can be found among the Abenaki people.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abenaki] A century later, fewer than 1,000 Abenaki remained after the American Revolution.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abenaki] In the 1990 US census, 1,549 people identified themselves as Abenaki.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abenaki] So did 2,544 people in the 2000 US census, with 6,012 people claiming Abenaki heritage.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abenaki] In 1991 Canadian Abenaki numbered 945; by 2006 they numbered 2,164.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abenaki] Lydia Maria Child wrote of the Abenaki in her short story, "The Church in the Wilderness" (1828).
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abenaki] Several Abenaki characters and much about their 18th-century culture are featured in the Kenneth Roberts' novel *Arundel* (1930).
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abenaki] The film *Northwest Passage* (1940) is based on a novel of the same name by Roberts.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abenaki] Letters and other nonfiction writing can be found in the anthology *Dawnland Voices*, edited by Siobhan Senier.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abenaki] Selections include letters from leader of the early praying town, Wamesit in Massachusetts Samuel Numphow, Sagamore Kancamagus, and writings on the Abenaki language by former chief of the reserve at Odanak in Quebec, Joseph Laurent, as well as many others.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abenaki] Accounts of life with the Abenaki can be found in the captivity narratives written by women taken captive by the Abenaki from the early New England settlements: Mary Rowlandson (1682), Hannah Duston (1702); Elizabeth Hanson (1728); Susannah Willard Johnson (1754); and Jemima Howe (1792).
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In the United States, abortion is a divisive issue in politics and culture wars.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Prior to the mid-19th century, English common law formed the basis of abortion law in the colonies and the early Republic.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Connecticut was the first state to regulate abortion in 1821; it outlawed abortion after quickening, the moment in pregnancy when the pregnant woman starts to feel the fetus's movement in the uterus, and forbade the use of poisons to induce one post-quickening.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Many states subsequently passed various laws on abortion until the Supreme Court of the United States decisions of *Roe v.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Bolton* decriminalized abortion nationwide in 1973.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The *Roe* decision imposed a federally mandated uniform framework for state legislation on the subject.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] It also established a minimal period during which abortion is legal, with more or fewer restrictions throughout the pregnancy.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] That basic framework, modified in *Planned Parenthood v.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Casey* (1992), remained nominally in place, although the effective availability of abortion varied significantly from state to state, as many counties had no abortion providers.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In 2022, *Roe* and *Casey* were overturned in *Dobbs v.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Jackson Women's Health Organization*, ending protection of abortion rights by the United States Constitution and allowing individual states to regulate any aspect of abortion not preempted by federal law.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Since 1976, the Republican Party has generally sought to restrict abortion access based on the stage of pregnancy or to criminalize abortion, whereas the Democratic Party has generally defended access to abortion and has made contraception easier to obtain.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The abortion-rights movement advocates for patient choice and bodily autonomy, while the anti-abortion movement advocate that the fetus has a right to live.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Historically framed as a debate between the pro-choice and pro-life labels, most Americans agree with some positions of each side.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Support for abortion gradually increased in the U.S. beginning in the early 1970s, and stabilized during the 2010s.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The abortion rate has continuously declined from a peak in 1980 of 30 per 1,000 women of childbearing age (15–44) to 11.3 by 2018.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In 2018, 78% of abortions were performed at 9 weeks or less gestation, and 92% of abortions were performed at 13 weeks or less gestation.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] By 2023, medication abortions accounted for 63% of all abortions.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Almost 25% of women will have had an abortion by age 45, with 20% of 30 year olds having had one.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In 2019, 60% of women who had abortions were already mothers, and 50% already had two or more children.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Increased access to birth control has been statistically linked to reductions in the abortion rate.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The first state to decriminalize abortion prior to *Roe* was Hawaii.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] As of 2025, Alaska, Arizona, California, Colorado, Illinois, Kansas, Maryland, Michigan, Minnesota, Missouri, Montana, New York, Ohio, Vermont, and Wyoming have a right to abortion in their state constitutions, either explicitly or as interpreted by the state supreme court.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Other states, such as Massachusetts and Oregon, protect abortion under state law.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The state constitutions of Alabama, Arkansas, Louisiana, Tennessee, and West Virginia explicitly contain no right to an abortion, while the state constitution of Nebraska prohibits abortion after the first trimester.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In medical parlance, "abortion" refers only to the end of an intrauterine pregnancy before the embryo or fetus can survive outside the uterus.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] This is inclusive of spontaneous abortion (more commonly referred to as miscarriage or early pregnancy loss) and to induced abortion, where a pregnancy is ended through medication or a medical procedure.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The abortion debate most commonly relates to the induced abortion of a pregnancy, which is also how the term "abortion" is used in a legal sense.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Because abortion has been politicized, there has been a proliferation of ill-defined, inconsistently applied terms with no medical or clinical basis.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Concepts like "late-term abortion", or "partial-birth abortion" are not medical terms and do not have clinical significance.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Similarly, terms like "elective abortion" append unnecessary qualifiers that are not rooted in medical or legal distinctions.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The American College of Obstetricians and Gynecologists recommends using the terms "induced abortion" or simply "abortion" instead.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Additionally, some drugs that do not induce medical abortions, such as levonorgestrel, have been referred to as abortifacients by a US Senator.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Abortion in what eventually became the United States was governed by English Common law, which held that abortion after quickening was murder.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] This was repeated by Henry de Bracton, Matthew Hale, and William Blackstone.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The common law on abortions before quickening was varying.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Some historians argue that abortion was a fairly common practice in the history of the United States, and was not always controversial.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] At a time when society was more concerned with the more serious consequence of women becoming pregnant out of wedlock, family affairs were handled out of public view.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Abortion did not become a public controversy until the health risk of unsafe abortions by (female) unlicensed practitioners was brought to the public attention in the 19th century.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] James Mohr wrote that even though pre-quickening abortion was legal in the first three decades of the 19th century, only 1 in 25 to 1 in 30 pregnancies ended in abortion.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] By the 1850s and 1860s, this number had increased to 1 in 5 or 1 in 6.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] John Keown highlighted some challenges in pinning down the common law view, observing that "evidence of quickening would clearly facilitate prosecution".
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In the mid-18th century, Benjamin Franklin included a recipe for an abortifacient in a math textbook.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In 1728, Franklin condemned publisher Samuel Keimer for publishing an article on abortion.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] According to biographer Walter Isaacson, Franklin did not have a strong view on the issue.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In *The Speech of Polly Baker*, Franklin places the blame for abortion and infanticide on the sexual double standard against women.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In 1716, New York passed an ordinance prohibiting midwives from providing abortion.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Founding Father and Second President of the United States John Adams praised the Spartan lawgiver Lycurgus for refusing his sister-in-law from having an abortion even though it prevented him from assuming power.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Thomas Jefferson wrote approving of a quote by Montesquieu that "‘there is among savages another custom . . . it is the cruel practice of abortion." Jefferson added that the Natives stopped the practice after becoming "civilized".
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Within the context of a sex scandal, Connecticut became the first state to regulate abortion by statute in 1821.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Many states subsequently passed various abortion laws.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In 1829, New York made post-quickening abortions a felony and pre-quickening abortions a misdemeanor.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] This was followed by 10 of the 26 states creating similar restrictions within the next few decades, in particular by the 1860s and 1870s.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The first laws related to abortion were made to protect women from real or perceived risks, and those more restrictive penalized only the provider.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Criminalization did not end the practice of abortion; unlicensed doctors and midwives continued to perform them.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Most of the women receiving abortions from unlicensed practitioners were poor.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Women's safety continued to be a concern, especially after the highly publicized death of Mary Rogers.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Wealthier women could pay willing physicians to broadly interpret health exceptions in their favor.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Euphemistic advertisements for abortifacients offered an assortment of herbal remedies.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] A number of other factors likely played a role in the rise of anti-abortion laws.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] As in Europe, abortion techniques advanced starting in the 17th century, and the conservatism of most in the medical profession with regards to sexual matters prevented the wide expansion of abortion techniques.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Physicians, who were the leading advocates of abortion criminalization laws, appear to have been motivated at least in part by advances in medical knowledge.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Science had discovered that fertilization inaugurated a more or less continuous process of development, which produced a new human being.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Quickening was found to be not more or less crucial in the process of gestation than any other step.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Many physicians concluded that if society considered it unjustifiable to terminate pregnancy after the fetus had quickened, and if quickening was a relatively unimportant step in the gestation process, then it was just as wrong to terminate a pregnancy before quickening as after quickening.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The doctors used flawed math to convince the American Medical Association to accept that pre-quickening abortion should also be outlawed, leading to the raft of state laws banning abortion in the latter half of the 19th century.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Doctors were also influenced by practical reasons to advocate anti-abortion laws.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] For one, abortion providers were usually female midwives without formal training or education.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In an age where the leading doctors in the nation were attempting to standardize the medical profession, these unlicensed practitioners were considered a nuisance to public health.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Despite campaigns to end the practice of abortion, abortifacient advertising was highly effective and abortion was commonly practiced, with the help of a midwife or other women, in the mid-19th century, although they were not always safe.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] While the precise abortion rate was not known, James Mohr's 1978 book *Abortion in America* documented multiple recorded estimates by 19th-century physicians, which suggested that between around 15% and 35% of all pregnancies ended in abortion during that period.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] This era also saw a marked shift in the people who were obtaining abortions.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Before the start of the 19th century, most abortions were sought by unmarried women, who had become pregnant out of wedlock and for which there was much less compassion compared to married women who got an abortion; many of them were wealthy and paid well.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Out of 54 abortion cases published in American medical journals between 1839 and 1880, over half were sought by married women, and well over 60% of the married women already had at least one child.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The sense that married women were now frequently obtaining abortions worried many conservative physicians, who were almost exclusively men.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In the Reconstruction era, much of the blame was placed on the burgeoning women's rights movement.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Although the medical profession expressed hostility toward feminism, many feminists of the era were also opposed to abortion.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In *The Revolution*, a newspaper operated by Elizabeth Cady Stanton and Susan B.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Anthony, an 1869 opinion piece was published arguing that instead of merely attempting to pass a law against abortion, the root cause must also be addressed.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The writer stated that simply passing an anti-abortion law would be "only mowing off the top of the noxious weed, while the root remains. ...
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] No matter what the motive, love of ease, or a desire to save from suffering the unborn innocent, the woman is awfully guilty who commits the deed.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] It will burden her conscience in life, it will burden her soul in death; But oh! thrice guilty is he who drove her to the desperation which impelled her to the crime." To many feminists of this era, abortion was regarded as an undesirable necessity forced upon women by thoughtless men.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The free love wing of the feminist movement refused to advocate for abortion and treated the practice as an example of the hideous extremes to which modern marriage was driving women.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Marital rape and the seduction of unmarried women were societal ills, which feminists believed caused the need to abort, as men did not respect women's right to abstinence.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Feminist opposition to abortion was much less prevalent by the 20th century, and it was feminists and physicians who came to question anti-abortion laws and raise public interest in the 1960s.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In 1873, Anthony Comstock created the New York Society for the Suppression of Vice, an institution dedicated to supervising the morality of the public.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Later that year, Comstock successfully influenced the United States Congress to pass the Comstock Law, which made it illegal to deliver through the U.S. mail any "obscene, lewd, or lascivious" material.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] It also prohibited producing or publishing information pertaining to the procurement of abortion, birth control, and venereal disease, including to medical students.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The production, publication, importation, and distribution of such materials was suppressed under the Comstock Law as being obscene, and similar prohibitions were passed by 24 of the 37 states.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] By 1900, abortion was normally a felony in every state.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Some states included provisions allowing for abortion in limited circumstances, generally to protect the woman's health or to terminate pregnancies arising from rape or incest.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Most Americans did not view abortion as a crime, and abortions continued to occur and became increasingly available.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The American Birth Control League was founded by Margaret Sanger in 1921; it would become Planned Parenthood Federation of America in 1942.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] By the 1930s, licensed physicians performed an estimated 800,000 abortions a year.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In 1988, 17 year old Becky Bell died from an infection after an unsafe abortion.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] She lived in Indiana where parental consent was required to have a safe and legal abortion.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Tribe wrote in *Abortion: The Clash of Absolutes* that Bell's best friend said that Becky considered an out-of-state abortion to get around Indiana's parental consent requirement.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] It is possible she performed the abortion herself.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] However it was done, Becky died from an infection that was probably caused by the procedure.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Her parents publicly campaigned against parental consent laws after her death.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Rosie Jimenez died from sepsis in 1977 following an abortion procedure at the home of a midwife who was not licensed to perform abortions.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] She did not go to a licensed physician because the Hyde Amendment barring public Medicaid funding for abortions had gone into effect after surviving a statutory challenge in *Beal v.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Doe* and an Equal Protection challenge in *Maher v.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Abu Hayat was convicted by a Manhattan Court in 1993 for performing an illegal third trimester abortion at his clinic in Alphabet City.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The doctor began the dilation and evacuation procedure which was not legal in the third trimester.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The baby was born alive before the procedure could be completed.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] She was missing an arm that had been severed during the D&E.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Hayat argued that he was protected from criminal conviction by *Roe v.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Wade* based on an argument that the baby had not yet been born when he attempted the procedure.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Another patient was forced to leave Hayat's clinic halfway through a procedure after Dr.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Hayat demanded more money that her husband could not afford to pay.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The patient nearly died and was treated at a local hospital for severe infection caused by pieces of dismembered fetus being left in her uterus.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] 17 year old Sophie McCoy died in 1990 from an infected uterine perforation after receiving an abortion at Dr.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Inequality in access to safe and legal abortions persists to this day whereby many women cannot afford to obtain a legal abortion; in such cases, women may turn to illegal abortion.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In the early 1960s, a controversy centered around children's television host Sherri Finkbine that helped bring abortion and abortion law more directly into the American public eye.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Living in the area of Phoenix, Arizona, Finkbine had had four healthy children; during her pregnancy with her fifth child, she discovered the child might have severe deformities when born.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] This was likely because Finkbine had been taking sleeping pills that she was unaware contained thalidomide, a drug that increases the risk of fetal deformities during pregnancy.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Though Finkbine wanted an abortion, the abortion laws of Arizona only allowed abortions if a pregnancy posed a threat to the woman's life.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The situation gained public attention after Finkbine shared the story with a reporter from *The Arizona Republic*, who disclosed her identity in spite of her requests for anonymity.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] On August 18, 1962, Finkbine traveled to Sweden to obtain a legal abortion, where it was confirmed that the fetus had severe deformities.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In 1964, Gerri Santoro of Connecticut died trying to obtain an illegal abortion, and her photo became the symbol of an abortion-rights movement.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Some women's rights activist groups developed their own skills to provide abortions to women who could not obtain them elsewhere.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] As an example, in Chicago, a group known as "Jane" operated a floating abortion clinic throughout much of the 1960s.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Women seeking the procedure would call a designated number and be given instructions on how to find "Jane".
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Connecticut* struck down one of the remaining contraception Comstock laws in Connecticut and Massachusetts.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] However, *Griswold* only applied to marital relationships, allowing married couples to buy and use contraceptives without government restriction.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Baird*, to extend the precedent of *Griswold* to unmarried persons as well.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In 1967, Colorado became the first state to decriminalize abortion in cases of rape, incest, or in which pregnancy would lead to permanent physical disability of the woman.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Similar laws were passed in California, Oregon, and North Carolina.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In 1970, Hawaii became the first state to legalize abortions on the request of the woman, and New York repealed its 1830 law and allowed abortions up to the 24th week of pregnancy.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Similar laws were soon passed in Alaska and Washington.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In 1970, Washington held a referendum on legalizing early pregnancy abortions, becoming the first state to legalize abortion through a vote of the people.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] A law in Washington, D.C., which allowed abortion to protect the life or health of the woman, was challenged in the Supreme Court in 1971 in *United States v.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The court upheld the law, deeming that "health" meant "psychological and physical well-being", essentially allowing abortion in Washington, D.C.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] By the end of 1972, 13 states had a law similar to that of Colorado, while Mississippi allowed abortion in cases of rape or incest only and Alabama and Massachusetts allowed abortions only in cases where the woman's physical health was endangered.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In order to obtain abortions during this period, women would often travel from a state where abortion was illegal to one where it was legal.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Wade* was that abortion was illegal in 30 states and legal under certain circumstances in 20 states.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Wade*, 30 states prohibited abortion without exception, 16 states banned abortion except in certain special circumstances (e.g. rape, incest, and health threat to mother), 3 states allowed residents to obtain abortions, and New York allowed abortions generally.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Early that year, on January 22, 1973, the U.S.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Wade* invalidated all of these laws, and set guidelines for the availability of abortion.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The decision returned abortion to its liberalized pre-1820 status.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] *Roe* established that the right of privacy of a woman to obtain an abortion "must be considered against important state interests in regulation".
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Wade*, the Court ruled that a Texas statute forbidding abortion except when necessary to save the life of the mother was unconstitutional.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The Court arrived at its decision by concluding that the issue of abortion and abortion rights falls under the right of privacy in the United States (e.g. federal constitutionally-protected right), in the sense of the right of a person not to be encroached by the state.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In its opinion, it listed several landmark cases where the court had previously found a right to privacy implied by the Constitution.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The Court did not recognize a right to abortion in all cases, saying: "State regulation protective of fetal life after viability thus has both logical and biological justifications.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The Court held that a right to privacy existed and included the right to have an abortion.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The court found that a mother had a right to abortion until viability, a point to be determined by the abortion doctor.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] After viability a woman can obtain an abortion for health reasons, which the Court defined broadly to include psychological well-being.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] A central issue in the *Roe* case and in the wider abortion debate in general is whether human life or personhood begins at conception, birth, or at some point in between.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The Court declined to make an attempt at resolving this issue, writing: "We need not resolve the difficult question of when life begins.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Rather than asserting that human life begins at any specific point, the Court declared that the state has a "compelling interest" in protecting "potential life" at the point of viability.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Wade*, state governments may not prohibit late terminations of pregnancy when "necessary to preserve the life or health of the mother", even if it would cause the demise of a viable fetus.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] This rule was clarified by the 1973 judicial decision *Doe v.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Bolton*, which specifies "that the medical judgment may be exercised in the light of all factors—physical, emotional, psychological, familial, and the woman's age—relevant to the well-being of the patient".
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] It is by this provision for the mother's mental health that women in the U.S. legally choose abortion after viability when screenings reveal abnormalities that do not cause a baby to die shortly after birth.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In the late 1960s, a number of organizations were formed to mobilize opinion both against and for the legalization of abortion.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In 1966, the National Conference of Catholic Bishops assigned Monsignor James T.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] McHugh to document efforts to reform abortion laws, and anti-abortion groups began forming in various states in 1967.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In 1968, McHugh led an advisory group which became the National Right to Life Committee.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The forerunner of the NARAL Pro-Choice America was formed in 1969 to oppose restrictions on abortion and expand access to abortion.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Wade*, in late 1973, NARAL became the National Abortion Rights Action League.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In the 1992 case of *Planned Parenthood v.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Casey*, the Court abandoned *Roe's* strict trimester framework but maintained its central holding that women have a right to choose to have an abortion before viability.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] *Roe* had held that statutes regulating abortion must be subject to "strict scrutiny"—the traditional Supreme Court test for impositions upon fundamental Constitutional rights.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The Supreme Court continues to make decisions on this subject.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] On April 18, 2007, it issued a ruling in the case of *Gonzales v.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Carhart*, involving a federal law entitled the Partial-Birth Abortion Ban Act of 2003 which President George W.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The law banned intact dilation and extraction, which opponents of abortion rights referred to as "partial-birth abortion", and stipulated that anyone breaking the law would get a prison sentence up to 2.5 years.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The United States Supreme Court upheld the 2003 ban by a narrow majority of 5–4, marking the first time the Court has allowed a ban on any type of abortion since 1973.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The opinion, which came from justice Anthony Kennedy, was joined by Justices Antonin Scalia, Clarence Thomas, and the two recent appointees, Samuel Alito and Chief Justice John Roberts.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Hellerstedt*, the Supreme Court in a 5–3 decision on June 27, 2016, swept away forms of state restrictions on the way abortion clinics can function.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The Court supported this argument and struck down these two provisions "facially" from the law at issue—that is, the very words of the provisions were invalid, no matter how they might be applied in any practical situation.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] According to the Supreme Court, the task of judging whether a law puts an unconstitutional burden on a woman's right to abortion belongs with the courts, and not the legislatures.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The Supreme Court ruled similarly in *June Medical Services, LLC v.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Russo* on June 29, 2020, in a 5–4 decision that a Louisiana state law, modeled after the Texas law at the center of *Whole Woman's Health*, was unconstitutional.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Like Texas' law, the Louisiana law required certain measures for abortion clinics that, if having gone into effect, would have closed five of the six clinics in the state.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The case in Louisiana was put on hold pending the result of *Whole Woman's Health*, and was retried based on the Supreme Court's decision.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] While the District Court ruled the law unconstitutional, the Fifth Circuit found that unlike the Texas law, the burden of the Louisiana law passed the tests outlined in *Whole Woman's Health*, and thus the law was constitutional.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The Supreme Court issued an order to suspend enforcement of the law pending further review, and agreed to hear the case in full in October 2019.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] It was the first abortion-related case to be heard by President Donald Trump's appointees to the Court, Neil Gorsuch and Brett Kavanaugh.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The Supreme Court found the Louisiana law unconstitutional for the same reasons as the Texas one, reversing the Fifth Circuit.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The judgment was supported by Chief Justice John Roberts who had dissented on *Whole Woman's Health* but joined in judgment as to upholding the court's respect for the past judgment in that case.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In December 2021, the FDA legalized telemedical provision of abortion pills with delivery by mail, after finding this to be safe and effective, and having suspended enforcement of previous restrictions during the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] As of June that year, 31 states allowed the practice, fourteen required the prescribing clinician to be physically present, which effectively banned telemedicine, and five explicitly banned telemedical abortion.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The Supreme Court granted *certiorari* to *Dobbs v.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Jackson Women's Health Organization* in May 2021, a case that challenges the impact of *Roe v.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Wade* in blocking enforcement of a 2018 Mississippi law (the Gestational Age Act) that had banned any abortions after the first 15 weeks.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Oral arguments to *Dobbs* were held in December 2021, and a decision was expected by the end of the 2021–22 Supreme Court term.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] On September 1, 2021, Texas passed the Texas Heartbeat Act, one of the most restrictive abortion laws in the nation, banning most procedures after six weeks.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] On May 2, 2022, a leaked draft majority opinion for *Dobbs*, written by Samuel Alito, set to overturn *Roe* was reported by *Politico*.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] On June 24, 2022, the Supreme Court overruled both *Roe* and *Planned Parenthood v.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Casey* in the *Dobbs* case on originalist grounds that a right to abortion cannot be found in the U.S.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] John Roberts, the Chief Justice of the United States, concurred in the decision to uphold the law at question as constitutional, by a 6–3 vote, but did not support overruling both *Roe* and *Casey*.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] This enabled trigger laws, which had been passed in 13 states, to ban abortions in those states.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Voters in Ohio defeated August 2023 Ohio Issue 1, which intended to make changes to the state's constitution more difficult.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] November 2023 Ohio Issue 1 was then approved by a majority of voters, which added the right to an abortion to the Ohio constitution.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Although states nominally allow abortion to prevent the woman's imminent death, five women have died to pregnancy related issues in Texas alone due to doctors refusing to perform abortions because of the state's abortion law despite the *de jure* legal circumstances.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In 2026, 2024 Nevada Question 6 needs to be approved again to enshrine abortion in the state's constitution, while legislators in Hawaii, Virginia, and the state of Washington proposed similar amendments to codify abortion rights in 2026.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Gerardo Flores was convicted of two counts of capital murder in 2005 under Texas' fetal homicide law.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] His girlfriend Erica Basoria testified that she had asked him to step on her stomach because her attempts to induce miscarriage on herself had been unsuccessful.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Flores said he initially refused but she would not relent until he agreed.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Flores admitted to police that he "accidentally, probably" hit Basoria in the face during a fight on the night of the miscarriage.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Basoria told police that he was not abusive.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Texas' fetal homicide law did not allow charges against the mother because she had a right to terminate pregnancy, so only Flores was charged.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In 2019 a woman in Alabama was indicted after she was shot in the stomach for intentionally causing the death of "unborn baby Jones by initiating a fight knowing she was five months pregnant".
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Medical abortion via mifepristone and misoprostol was approved for abortion in the United States by the FDA in September 2000.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] As of 2007, it was legal and available in all 50 states, Washington, D.C., Guam, and Puerto Rico.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] It is a prescription drug, but was not initially available to the public through pharmacies; its distribution is primarily restricted to specially qualified licensed physicians, sold by Danco Laboratories under the brand name Mifeprex.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] French pharmaceutical company Roussel-Uclaf, (the company that synthesized mifepristone in 1980 and took it through clinical trials for approval in France by 1988) did not seek US approval, so in the United States legal availability was not initially possible.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The United States banned importation of mifepristone for personal use in 1989, a decision supported by Roussel Uclaf.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In 1994, Roussel Uclaf gave the U.S. drug rights to the Population Council in exchange for immunity from any product liability claims.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The Population Council sponsored clinical trials in the United States.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The drug went on approvable status from 1996.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Production was intended to begin through the Danco Group in 1996, but they withdrew briefly in 1997 due to a corrupt business partner, delaying availability again.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Mifepristone was approved for abortion in the United States by the FDA in September 2000.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In 2016, the US Food and Drug Administration (FDA) approved mifepristone, to end a pregnancy through 70 days gestation (70 days or less since the first day of a woman's last menstrual period).
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The approved dosing regimen is 200 mg of mifepristone taken by mouth (swallowed).
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] 24 to 48 hours after taking mifepristone, 800 mcg (micrograms) of misoprostol is taken buccally (in the cheek pouch), at a location appropriate for the patient.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] As of September 2021, in 32 states, the drug could only be provided by a licensed physician, and in 19 states, the prescribing clinician was required to be physically in the room with the patient while they are taking the drug.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In the midst of the COVID-19 pandemic on December 16, 2021, in light of the difficulties in accessing in-person healthcare services, the FDA approved the distribution of mifepristone via mail.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] On 16 December 2021, the FDA voluntarily adopted a new rule permanently relaxing the requirement that the pill be obtained in person, allowing it to be sent through the mail.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] A prescription is still required, so that a doctor can screen for risk factors that would make taking the pill unsafe for the mother.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In January 2023, the FDA further relaxed rules, allowing any retail pharmacy to become certified to fill mifepristone prescriptions.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Department of Justice stated that USPS mailing of pills for medication abortion, even into states where abortion services are restricted, does not violate federal law.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In 2023, online access to abortion medication by mail delivered by the U.S.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Postal Service is currently available to citizens of all states.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In light of the *Dobbs* decision, the Alliance Defending Freedom launched a lawsuit in November 2022 in the Northern District of Texas under Judge Matthew J.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Kacsmaryk to seek to overturn the FDA's original approval of mifepristone.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Judge Kacsmaryk ruled for the Alliance on April 7, 2023, reversing the FDA's approval and banning mifepristone across the United States after seven days.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] A district judge in a separate lawsuit, Thomas O.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Rice of the Eastern District of Washington, ruled that the FDA should not reverse access to mifepristone in 16 states.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Kacsmaryk's ruling was partially reversed by a panel on the Fifth Circuit Court of Appeals, leaving mifepristone on the market but reverting efforts made by the FDA to liberalize its use over seven years.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The case was appealed to the Supreme Court, and on June 13, 2024, the court ruled that the Alliance Defending Freedom lacked standing to bring the suit.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In January 2023, GenBioPro filed suit to overturn state laws that prohibit sale of mifepristone, claiming that such laws are invalid because it is a federally approved drug.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The argument that state laws seeking to ban or restrict the use of mifepristone are preempted by the FDA's decision to make the drug available is supported by a number of Supreme Court decisions, including opinions by the traditionally more conservative Justices.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In March 2023, Wyoming became the first US state to ban the pill.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In April 2023, in a lawsuit brought by 17 US states and the District of Columbia, federal district judge Thomas O.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Rice issued a temporary injunction that the FDA should not reduce access to mifepristone in these states and the district.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In May 2024, the state of Louisiana classified mifepristone and misoprostol as controlled substances, with penalties for possession without a prescription.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The move follows concerns over coerced abortion and has drawn criticism from over 240 doctors in the state.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In December 2025, the states of Florida and Texas filed a lawsuit against the FDA challenging its approval of mifepristone in 2000 and approval of a generic in 2025.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] After regulations on abortion early in pregnancy were ruled constitutional by the 2022 decision *Dobbs v.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Jackson Women's Health Organization*, some states enacted restrictions on abortions and abortion pills.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In January 2023, the United States Department of Justice issued an interpretation of the Comstock Act that it was legal for United States Postal Service employees to deliver the pills in any state, because they could not know whether the pills would be used for an abortion or other purposes.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Alliance for Hippocratic Medicine* lawsuit, federal district judge Matthew J.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Kacsmaryk issued a preliminary injunction suspending the 2000 approval of mifepristone, which would take effect a week later.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The Fifth Circuit reversed parts of Kacsmaryk's injunction, but placed a temporary injunction on the 2016 REMS change to mifepristone.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] On appeal to the Supreme Court, the Court stayed both injunctions on 21 April 2023, with only Justices Samuel Alito and Clarence Thomas stating their dissent.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The stay allowed mifepristone to remain legally available while the lower courts consider the merits of the case.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In June 2024, the US Supreme Court unanimously overturned judge Kacsmaryk's Fifth Circuit decision on the grounds that the Alliance for Hippocratic Medicine had no standing to challenge the FDA's regulations of mifepristone.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The Supreme Court ruled that Alliance for Hippocratic Medicine did not demonstrate that they would suffer harm to warrant standing.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The Court did not rule on the substance of mifepristone, abortion, or the FDA's procedures.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Some drugs are approved by the FDA under subsection H, which has two subparts.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The first sets forth ways to rush experimental drugs, such as aggressive HIV and cancer treatments, to market when speedy approval is deemed vital to the health of potential patients.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The second part of subsection H applies to drugs that not only must meet restrictions for use due to safety requirements, but also are required to meet postmarketing surveillance to establish that the safety results shown in clinical trials are seconded by use in a much wider population.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Until December 2021, Mifepristone was approved under the second part of subsection H.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The result is that women could not pick the drug up at a pharmacy, but were required to receive it directly from a doctor.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The approval of mifepristone under subsection H included a black box warning.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] During the COVID pandemic, and coupled with growing restrictions on abortion access in conservative states, the FDA performed trial runs of telemedical abortions, allowing doctors to prescribe mifepristone and other medical abortion drugs without an in-person visit by the patient.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] By December 2021, the FDA advanced approval to for telemedical abortions for all registered providers. which was made final by 2023.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] As of July 2025, 25 states allowed telemedical abortions, the prescription of medical abortion drugs without an in-person visit to a doctor, without restriction, 13 states allowed abortion but had restrictions on telemedical abortions, and 12 states banned abortion.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The FDA's action, coupled with the *Dobbs* decision, led many conservative states to seek new laws to ban citizens in their states from telemedical abortion, or seeking penalties from those that prescribe that medication from other states.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] As a result, eight states where telemedical abortion was legal passed shield laws shield laws to enable physicians to remotely prescribe abortion medication to patients in states where abortion is banned.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] In October 2025, Louisiana Attorney General Liz Murrill and the Alliance Defending Freedom filed Louisiana v.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] FDA against the Food and Drug Administration and Department of Health and Human Services challenging the 2023 Risk Evaluation and Mitigation Strategies (REMS) for mifepristone which removed the in-person dispensing requirement.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The Republican Attorneys General of 21 states filed in support of Louisiana's lawsuit.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The lawsuit is one of several brought by Republican Attorneys General seeking to restrict mifepristone.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Joseph paused the case while the second Trump administration conducts a review of the 2023 REMS.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] On May 1, 2026, Republican-appointed Judges Kyle Duncan, Leslie H.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] Engelhardt on the Fifth Circuit Court of Appeals unanimously blocked the 2023 REMS, preventing the mailing of mifepristone country-wide.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] However, the Supreme Court temporarily lifted the Fifth Circuit's order via the shadow docket on May 4, and stayed it for an indefinite period on May 14, over dissent from Alito and Thomas.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p01] The ruling will remain in effect through at least the course of the Louisiana-FDA lawsuit, which is expected to continue into the year 2027.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Beyond limitations pertaining to abortion in the context of federal funding, there is little federal legislation protecting or penalizing abortion in the United States.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] The Partial-Birth Abortion Ban Act of 2003, Freedom of Access to Clinic Entrances Act of 1994, and Comstock Act of 1873 are some of the few pieces of existing federal law that provide substantive criminal provisions either protecting or penalizing abortion.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] The provisions in the Partial Birth Abortion Ban Act and the Freedom of Access to Clinic Entrances Act cover activity affecting interstate or foreign commerce, to which the former was upheld (against constitutional attack under the 5th amendment) by the Supreme Court in *Gonzales v.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] The provisions of the Comstock Act primarily cover activity using the mail or postal system, and the Comstock Act was first upheld by Supreme Court in *Ex parte Jackson* (1878).
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] The legality of abortion is frequently a major issue in nomination battles for the U.S.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Nominees typically remain silent on the issue during their hearings, as the issue may come before them as judges.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] In 2021, the Women's Health Protection Act, which would protect abortion rights by federal statute, was introduced by Judy Chu.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] House of Representatives but was rejected by the U.S.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] After the *Dobbs* decision, Merrick Garland, then-U.S.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Attorney General, asserted that under federal law, states do not have the power to restrict access to FDA-approved abortion pills.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Currently, 13 states have criminal penalties for performing abortions, regardless of gestational age.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] The penalties in states that have made abortion illegal vary, as outlined below.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] This chart lists only the penalties authorized specifically by the state laws which explicitly restrict (or ban) abortions.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] The chart does not address the risk of being prosecuted for violating any other law because of the abortion.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] States with criminal penalties that are blocked by a court or have yet to take effect are denoted by a gray background.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Prior to 2021, abortion was legal in all U.S. states, and every state had at least one abortion clinic.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Abortion is a controversial political issue, and regular attempts to restrict it occur in most states.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Two such cases, originating in Texas and Louisiana, led to the Supreme Court cases of *Whole Woman's Health v.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Hellerstedt* (2016) and *June Medical Services, LLC v.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Russo* (2020) in which several Texas and Louisiana restrictions were struck down.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] The issue of minors and abortion is regulated at the state level, and 37 states require some parental involvement, either in the form of parental consent or in the form of parental notification.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] In certain situations, the parental restrictions can be overridden by a court.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Mandatory waiting periods, mandatory ultrasounds and scripted counseling are common abortion regulations.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Abortion laws are generally stricter in conservative Southern states than they are in other parts of the country.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] In 2019, New York passed the Reproductive Health Act (RHA), which repealed a pre-*Roe* provision that banned third-trimester abortions except in cases where the continuation of the pregnancy endangered a pregnant woman's life.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Abortion in the Northern Mariana Islands, a United States Commonwealth territory, is illegal.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Alabama House Republicans passed a law on April 30, 2019, that will criminalize most abortion if it goes into effect.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Dubbed the "Human Life Protection Act", it offers only two exceptions: serious health risk to the mother or a lethal fetal anomaly.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Amendments that would have added cases of rape or incest to the list of exceptions were rejected It will also make the procedure a Class A felony.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Twenty-five male Alabama senators voted to pass the law on May 13.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] The next day, Alabama governor Kay Ivey signed the bill into law, primarily as a symbolic gesture in hopes of challenging *Roe v.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Since Alabama introduced the first modern anti-abortion legislation in April 2019, five other states have also adopted abortion laws including Mississippi, Kentucky, Ohio, Georgia and most recently Louisiana on May 30, 2019.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Supreme Court upheld an Indiana state law that requires fetuses which were aborted be buried or cremated.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] In a December 2019 case, the court declined to review a lower court decision which upheld a Kentucky law requiring doctors to perform ultrasounds and show fetal images to patients before abortions.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] On June 29, 2020, previous Supreme Court rulings banning abortion restrictions appeared to be upheld when the U.S.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Supreme Court struck down the Louisiana anti-abortion law.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Following the ruling, the legality of laws restricting abortion in states such as Ohio was then called into question.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] It was also noted that Supreme Court Chief Justice John Roberts, who agreed that the Louisiana anti-abortion law was unconstitutional, had previously voted to uphold a similar law in Texas which was struck down by the U.S.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] In order to avoid traditional constitutional challenges based on *Roe v.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Plaintiffs sought an order from the U.S.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Supreme Court to stop the law from coming into effect, but the Court issued a denial of the order late on September 1, 2021, allowing the law to remain in effect.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] While unsigned, Chief Justice John Roberts and Justice Stephen Breyer wrote dissenting opinions joined by Justices Elena Kagan and Sonia Sotomayor that they would have granted an injunction on the law until a proper judicial review.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Garland further noted that the United States government has "an obligation to ensure that no state can deprive individuals of their constitutional rights." The Complaint avers that Texas enacted the law "in open defiance of the Constitution".
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] District Court in Austin, Texas includes a declaration that the Texas Act is unconstitutional, and an injunction against state actors as well as any and all private individuals who may bring a SB 8 action.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] The idea of asking a federal court to impose an injunction upon the entire civilian population of a state is unprecedented and has drawn eyebrows.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] In April 2022 Colorado passed into law its Reproductive Health Equity Act, which assures abortion rights for all citizens of the state.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] On May 25, 2022, Oklahoma imposed a ban on almost all abortions after Oklahoma Governor Kevin Stitt signed House Bill 4327.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] The bill bans abortion beginning at conception, with exceptions only in cases of "rape, sexual assault, or incest that has been reported to law enforcement", or if "the abortion is necessary to save the life of a pregnant woman in a medical emergency".
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] The law also permits private citizens to file lawsuits against (1) abortion providers (2) any individual who "aids and abets" an induced abortion, including paying for an abortion through insurance or otherwise, or (3) any individuals who *intend* to provide or to aid and abet an induced abortion.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] A lawsuit was immediately filed by the ACLU in opposition to the bill.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] At the time of enactment, Oklahoma was the only U.S. state to have passed a bill imposing such restrictions; the law made Oklahoma the first U.S. state to ban induced abortion procedures since prior to the ruling and implementation of *Roe* in 1973.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] on June 24, 2022, after the Supreme Court overturned *Roe*, Texas and Missouri immediately banned abortions with the exception only if the pregnancy was deemed to be particularly life-threatening.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] On January 28, 2023, the Minnesota state Senate passed a bill guaranteeing women's rights to abortion and other reproductive medicine which was signed into law on January 31.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] The bill prohibits state and local governments from attempting to restrict access to sterilization or prenatal care, while also requiring contraceptive cost compensation.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] In June 2024 abortion in Iowa was made illegal after 6 weeks of gestation, with exceptions for rape, incest, foetal abnormalities, and the mother's life.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] In 2023, five women launched a class action lawsuit against the State of Texas after they were reportedly denied abortions at a clinic in the State despite grave risks to their life.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Four of the women traveled out of state in order to obtain an abortion, while the fifth only received the abortion in Texas when she was hospitalized after the fetus suffered a premature rupture of membranes.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] The case argues that the Texas law, which allows abortion if there is a health risk to the mother, is too vague and doctors will not perform an abortion for fear of legal repercussions.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Amid the COVID-19 pandemic, anti-abortion government officials in several American states enacted or attempted to enact restrictions on abortion, characterizing it as a non-essential procedure that can be suspended during the medical emergency.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] The orders have led to several legal challenges and criticism by human rights groups and several national medical organizations, including the American Medical Association.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Legal challenges on behalf of abortion providers, many of which were represented by the American Civil Liberties Union and Planned Parenthood, successfully stopped most of the orders on a temporary basis.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] One challenge was made against the FDA's rule on the distribution of mifepristone (RU-486), one of the two-part drug regimen to induce abortions.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Since 2000, it is only available through health providers under the FDA's ruling.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Due to the COVID-19 pandemic, access to mifepristone was a concern, and the American College of Obstetricians and Gynecologists along with other groups sued to have the rule relaxed to allow women to be able to access mifepristone at home through mail-order or retail pharmacies.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] While the Fourth Circuit issued a preliminary injunction against the FDA's ruling that would have allowed wider distribution, the Supreme Court ordered in a 6–3 decision in January 2021 to put a stay on the injunction, maintaining the FDA's rule.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Since 2019, the anti-abortion movement in the United States has sought declarations of "sanctuary cit[ies] for the unborn".
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] In June 2019, the city council of Waskom, Texas, voted to outlaw abortion in the city, declaring Waskom a "sanctuary city for the unborn" (the first such city to designate itself as such), as state governments elsewhere in the United States were also drafting abortion bans.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] As of July 2019, there is no abortion clinic in the city.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] The Waskom ordinance has led other small cities in Texas, and as of April 2021 in Nebraska, to vote in favor of becoming "sanctuary cities for the unborn".
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] On April 6, 2021, Hayes Center, Nebraska, became the first city in Nebraska to outlaw abortion by local ordinance, declaring itself a "sanctuary city for the unborn." The city of Blue Hill, Nebraska, followed suit and enacted a similar ordinance outlawing abortion on April 13, 2021.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] In May 2021, Lubbock, Texas, with a population of less than 270,000, voted to ban abortion with the "sanctuary city for the unborn ordinance", becoming the largest city in the U.S. to ban abortion.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Abortion rights movements have also pushed for similar counterpart legislation in other cities.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] The abortion debate has also been extended to the question of who pays the medical costs of the procedure, with some states using the mechanism as a way of reducing the number of abortions.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] The cost of an abortion varies depending on factors such as location, facility, timing, type of procedure, and whether or not there is insurance or some other type of financial assistance.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] In 2022, a medication abortion cost was about $580 at Planned Parenthood, though it could be more, up to around $800, in other facilities.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] During the first trimester an in-clinic abortion cost up to around $800, though often less; the average cost at Planned Parenthood was about $600.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] A second trimester procedure varied depending on the stage of pregnancy.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] The average ranged from about $715 earlier in the second trimester to $1,500–2,000 later in the second trimester.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] A variety of resources from support organizations are available to contribute to the costs of the procedure, as well as travel expenses.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] A variety of organizations offer financial support for people seeking abortions, including travel and other expenses.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Access Reproductive Care–Southeast (ARC Southeast), the Brigid Alliance, the Midwest Access Coalition (MAC), and the National Network of Abortion Funds are examples of such groups.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] The Hyde Amendment is a federal legislative provision barring the use of federal Medicaid funds to pay for abortions except for rape and incest.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] The provision, in various forms, was in response to *Roe v.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Wade*, and has been routinely attached to annual appropriations bills since 1976, and represented the first major legislative success by the pro-life movement.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] The law requires that states cover abortions under Medicaid in the event of rape, incest, and life endangerment.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Under this policy, U.S. federal funding to NGOs that provide abortion is not permitted.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] The policy was first announced by President Ronald Reagan in 1984.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] It has been rescinded by Democratic presidents and reinstated by Republican presidents.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] The policy was rescinded in 2021 by President Joe Biden and reinstated on January 24, 2025, by President Donald Trump.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Qualifying requirements for performing abortions vary from state to state.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Vermont has allowed physician assistants to do some first-trimester abortions since the mid-1970s.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] More recently, several states have changed their requirements for abortion providers, anticipating that the Supreme Court would overturn *Roe v.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Wade*; now that the court has done so, more states are expanding eligibility to provide abortions.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] In other states, non-physicians are not permitted to perform abortions.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Because reporting of abortions is not mandatory, statistics are of varying reliability.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Both the Centers For Disease Control (CDC) and the Guttmacher Institute regularly compile these statistics.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] However, in 2024 the Guttmacher Institute raised alarm that the Trump administration has severely gutted CDC efforts to collect these data.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] The annual number of legal induced abortions in the U.S. doubled between 1973 and 1979, and peaked in 1990.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] There was a slow but steady decline throughout the 1990s.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Overall, the number of annual abortions decreased by 6% between 2000 and 2009, with temporary spikes in 2002 and 2006.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] By 2011, abortion rate in the nation dropped to its lowest point since the Supreme Court legalized the procedure.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] According to a study performed by Guttmacher Institute, long-acting contraceptive methods had a significant impact in reducing unwanted pregnancies.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] There were fewer than 17 abortions for every 1,000 women of child-bearing age.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] That was a 13%-decrease from 2008's numbers and slightly higher than the rate in 1973, when the Supreme Court's *Roe v.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] The study indicated a long-term decline in the abortion rate.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] In 2016, the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) reported 623,471 abortions, a 2% decrease from 636,902 in 2015.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] During the first six months of 2023 (following *Dobbs* in 2022), the numbers of abortions in certain U.S. states changed dramatically compared to the same time period in 2020, according to the Guttmacher Institute.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Abortions tripled in New Mexico and Wyoming and more than doubled in South Carolina and Kansas.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] For 13 states that had banned abortion, the Guttmacher Institute had no 2023 data to make the comparison.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] A Guttmacher Institute survey of abortion providers estimated that early medical abortions accounted for 17% of all non-hospital abortions and slightly over one-quarter of abortions before 9 weeks gestation in the United States in 2008.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Medical abortions accounted for 32% of first-trimester abortions at Planned Parenthood clinics in 2008.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] By 2020, medication abortions accounted for more than 50% of all abortions.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] In 2023, medication abortions obtained within the formal health care system had risen to 63% of all abortions, with the total percentage (which would include self-managed abortions by individuals in states with total bans) likely higher.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] A majority of abortions are obtained by religiously identified women.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] According to the Guttmacher Institute, "more than 7 in 10 U.S. women obtaining an abortion report a religious affiliation (37% Protestant, 28% Catholic, and 7% other), and 25% attend religious services at least once a month.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Abortion rates tend to be higher among minority women in the United States.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] In 2000–2001, the rates among black and Hispanic women were 49 per 1,000 and 33 per 1,000, respectively, vs.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] 13 per 1,000 among non-Hispanic white women.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] This figure includes all women of reproductive age, including women that are not pregnant.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] In other words, these abortion rates reflect the rate at which U.S. women of reproductive age have an abortion each year.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] In 2004, the rates of abortion by ethnicity in the U.S. were 50 abortions per 1,000 black women, 28 abortions per 1,000 Hispanic women, and 11 abortions per 1,000 white women.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Wade legalized abortion nationwide in 1973.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] In 1972, 41% of abortions were performed on women outside their state of residence, while in 1973 it declined to 21%, and then to 11% in 1974.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] In the decade from 2011 to 2020, during which many states increased abortion restrictions, the percentage of women nationwide who traveled out of state for an abortion increased steadily, from 6% in 2011 to 9% in 2020.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Out of state travel for an abortion was much more prevalent in the 29 states hostile to abortion rights, with percentages in those states rising from 9% in 2011 to 15% by 2020, while in states supportive of abortion rights, out of state travel for abortions rose from 2% to 3% between 2011 and 2020.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] In 2024, around 155,000 people crossed state lines for abortions, doubling the number in 2020.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] In several states the percentage of abortions performed within the state specifically for people who traveled from outside of the state exceeds 15%, with Kansas, New Mexico, and Washington DC exceeding 50%.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Illinois performed the most out-of-state abortions in the US at 23% or 34,900 cases.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] In contrast, from 2017 to 2020, the *abortion rate by state of residence* for Missourians went up by 18% from 8.4 to 9.9.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Some out of state travel pertains to locations of population centers in states; if large cities are close to state borders it may be common to cross borders for an abortion.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] For example, Delaware, which is generally supportive of abortion rights, saw 44% of residents obtain their abortions in neighboring states.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] The source of this information takes findings into account from 27 nations including the United States, and therefore, these findings may not be typical for any one nation.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] In 2000, cases of rape or incest accounted for 1% of abortions.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] A 2008 National Survey of Family Growth (NSFG) shows that rates of unintended pregnancy are highest among Blacks, Hispanics, and women with lower socio-economic status.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] According to the Centers for Disease Control, in 2011, most (64.5%) abortions were performed by ≤8 weeks' gestation, and nearly all (91.4%) were performed by ≤13 weeks' gestation.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Few abortions (7.3%) were performed between 14 and 20 weeks' gestation or at ≥21 weeks' gestation (1.4%).
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] From 2002 to 2011, the percentage of all abortions performed at ≤8 weeks' gestation increased 6%.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] The risk of death from carrying a child to term in the U.S. is approximately 14 times greater than the risk of death from a legal abortion.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] In 2012, the mortality rate from legal abortion was 0.6 abortion-related deaths per 100,000 abortions.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] The risk of abortion-related mortality increases with gestational age, but remains lower than that of childbirth through at least 21 weeks' gestation.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] For the period 2013 – 2019, the rate of mortality from legal abortion procedures in the US was 0.43 abortion-related deaths per 100,000 reported legal abortions, lower than the rates for previous 5-year periods.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] In 2019, there were four identified deaths related to abortion in the US, out of 625,000 abortions.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] As an element of family planning, birth control was federally subsidized for low income families in 1965 under President Lyndon B.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] In 1970, Congress passed Title X to provide family planning services for those in need, and President Richard Nixon signed it into law.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] Funding for Title X rose from $6 million in 1971 to $61 million the next year, and slowly increased each year to $317 million in 2010, after which it was reduced by a few percent.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] In 2011, the Guttmacher Institute reported that the number of abortions in the U.S. would be nearly two-thirds higher without access to birth control.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p02] In 2015, the Federation of American Scientists reported that federally mandated access to birth control had helped reduce teenage pregnancies in the U.S. by 44 percent, and had prevented more than 188,000 unintended pregnancies.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] The level of support for access to abortion has been relatively consistent since 1972.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] Large majorities (over 75%) support access to abortion in "traumatic" cases (rape, danger to the mother's health, or strong chance of birth defects) and approximately 40-50% support elective abortion.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] Americans have been equally divided on the issue; a May 2018 Gallup poll indicated that 48% of Americans described themselves as "pro-choice" and 48% described themselves as "pro-life".
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] A July 2018 poll indicated that 64% of Americans did not want the Supreme Court to overturn *Roe v.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] The same poll found that support for abortion being generally legal was 60% during the first trimester of pregnancy, dropping to 28% in the second trimester, and 13% in the third trimester.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] In January 2013, a majority of Americans believed abortion should be legal in all or most cases, according to a poll by NBC News and *The Wall Street Journal*.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] Approximately 70% of respondents in the same poll opposed *Roe v.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] A poll by the Pew Research Center yielded similar results.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] Moreover, 48% of Republicans opposed overturning *Roe*, compared to 46% who supported overturning it.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] Gallup declared in May 2010 that more Americans identifying as "pro-life" is "the new normal", while also noting that there had been no increase in opposition to abortion.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] It suggested that political polarization may have prompted more Republicans to call themselves "pro-life".
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] The terms "pro-choice" and "pro-life" do not always reflect a political view or fall along a binary; in one Public Religion Research Institute poll, seven in ten Americans described themselves as "pro-choice" while almost two-thirds described themselves as "pro-life".
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] The same poll found that 56% of Americans were in favor of legal access to abortion in all or some cases.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] 90% approve of abortion when the health of the woman is endangered, 77.4% when there is a strong chance of defects in the baby that could result from the pregnancy, and 79.5% when the pregnancy is the result of rape.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] A 2022 poll by the Pew Research Center, found that 47% polled said that women who had an illegal abortion should face a penalty.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] 14% said they should face jail time, 16% said a fine or community services and 17% were not sure the penalty.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] Wade and significantly reduced access to abortion, dissatisfaction with the country's abortion policies rose to 69% (the highest level in 23 years), of which 46% want fewer restrictions on abortion, a significant increase from previous years.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] Since then, a consistent majority of the public has identified as pro-choice, with 52% identifying as pro-choice and 44% as pro-life in May 2023.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] Pew Research Center polling shows little change in views from 2008 to 2012; modest differences based on gender or age.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] The original article's table also shows by party affiliation, religion, and education level.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] Support for the legalization of abortion is significantly higher among more educated adults than less educated, and has been consistently so for decades.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] In 2019, 70% of college graduates support abortion being legal in all or most cases, as well as 60% of those with some college education, compared to 54% of those with a high school degree or less.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] A January 2003 CBS News/*The New York Times* poll examined whether Americans thought abortion should be legal or not, and found variations in opinion which depended upon party affiliation and the region of the country.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] The margin of error is +/– 4% for questions answered of the entire sample (overall figures) and may be higher for questions asked of subgroups (all other figures).
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] A January 2026 poll by Pew Research found that support for legal abortion in the U.S. varies by race.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] Polls indicates general support of legal abortion during the first trimester, although support drops dramatically for abortion during the second and third trimester.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] Since the 2011 poll, support for legal abortion during the first trimester has declined.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] According to Gallup's long-time polling on abortion, the majority of Americans are neither strictly "pro-life" or "pro-choice"; it depends upon the circumstances of the pregnancy.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] Gallup polling from 1996 to 2021 consistently reveals that when asked the question, "Do you think abortions should be legal under any circumstances, legal only under certain circumstances, or illegal in all circumstances?", Americans repeatedly answer "legal only under certain circumstances".
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] According to the poll, in any given year 48–57% say legal only under certain circumstances, 21–34% say legal under any circumstances, and 13–19% illegal in all circumstances, with 1–7% having no opinion.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] According to the aforementioned poll, Americans differ drastically based upon situation of the pregnancy, suggesting they do not support unconditional abortions.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] Congress outlawed intact dilation and extraction when it passed the Partial-Birth Abortion Ban Act.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] A Rasmussen Reports poll four days after the Supreme Court's opinion in *Gonzales v.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] Carhart* found that 40% of respondents "knew the ruling allowed states to place some restrictions on specific abortion procedures." Of those who knew of the decision, 56% agreed with the decision and 32% were opposed.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] An ABC poll from 2003 found that 62% of respondents thought "partial-birth abortion" should be illegal; a similar number of respondents wanted an exception "if it would prevent a serious threat to the woman's health".
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] Gallup has repeatedly queried the American public on this issue.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] After *Roe*, there was a national political realignment surrounding abortion.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] The abortion-rights movement in the United States initially emphasized the national policy benefits of abortion, such as smaller welfare expenses, slower population growth, and fewer illegitimate births.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] The abortion-rights movement drew support from the population control movement, feminists, and environmentalists.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] Anti-abortion advocates and civil-rights activists accused abortion-rights supporters of intending to control the population of racial minorities and the disabled, citing their ties to racial segregationists and eugenicist legal reformers.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] The abortion-rights movement subsequently distanced from the population control movement, and responded by taking up choice-based and rights-oriented rhetoric similar to what was used in the *Roe* decision.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] Opponents of abortion experienced a political shift.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] The Catholic Church and the Democratic Party supported an expansive welfare state, wanted to reduce rates of abortion through prenatal insurance and federally funded day care, and opposed abortion at the time of *Roe*.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] Afterwards, the anti-abortion movement in the United States shifted more to Protestant faiths that saw abortion rights as part of a liberal-heavy agenda to fight against, and became part of the new Christian right.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] The Protestant influence helped make opposition to abortion part of the Republican Party's platform by the 1990s.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] Republican-led states enacted laws to restrict abortion, including abortions earlier than *Casey*'s general standard of 24 weeks.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] Into the 21st century, although members of both major U.S. political parties come down on either side of the issue, the Republican Party is often seen as being anti-abortion, since the official party platform opposes abortion and considers fetuses to have an inherent right to life.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] Republicans for Choice represents the minority of that party.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] In 2006, pollsters found that 9% of Republicans favor the availability of abortion in most circumstances.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] Of Republican National Convention delegates in 2004, 13% believed that abortion should be generally available, and 38% believed that it should not be permitted.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] The same poll showed that 17% of all Republican voters believed that abortion should be generally available to those who want it, while 38% believed that it should not be permitted.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] The Democratic Party platform considers abortion to be a woman's right.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] Democrats for Life of America represents the minority of that party.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] In 2006, pollsters found that 74% of Democrats favor the availability of abortion in most circumstances.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] Of Democratic National Convention delegates in 2004, 75% believed that abortion should be generally available, and 2% believed that abortion should not be permitted.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] The same poll showed that 49% of all Democratic voters believed that abortion should be generally available to those who want it, while 13% believed that it should not be permitted.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] The position of U.S. third political parties and other U.S. minor political parties is diverse.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] The Green Party supports legal abortion as a woman's right.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] The Constitution Party is opposed to abortion.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] The issue of abortion has become deeply politicized.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] In 2002, 84% of state Democratic platforms supported the right to having an abortion while 88% of state Republican platforms opposed it.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] This divergence also led to Christian right organizations like Christian Voice, Christian Coalition of America, and Moral Majority having an increasingly strong role in the Republican Party.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] The policy was revoked by President Bill Clinton and subsequently reinstated by President George W.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] President Barack Obama overruled this policy by Executive Order on January 23, 2009, and it was reinstated on January 23, 2017, by President Donald Trump.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] On January 28, 2021, President Joe Biden signed a Presidential Memorandum that repealed the restoration of Mexico City policy and also called for the United States Department of Health and Human Services to "suspend, rescind or revoke" restrictions made to Title X.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] President Donald Trump reinstated the policy on January 24, 2025.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] The risk of death due to legal abortion has fallen considerably since *Roe v.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] Wade* (1973) legalized it; this was due to increased physician skills, improved medical technology, and earlier termination of pregnancy.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] From 1940 through 1970, annual deaths of pregnant women during abortion fell from nearly 1,500 to a little over 100.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] According to the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention, the number of women who died in 1972 from illegal abortion was thirty-nine.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] The Roe effect is a hypothesis suggesting that since supporters of abortion rights cause the erosion of their own political base by having fewer children, the practice of abortion will eventually lead to the restriction or illegalization of abortion.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] The legalized abortion and crime effect is another controversial theory that posits legal abortion reduces crime because unwanted children are more likely to become criminals.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] Since *Roe*, there have been numerous attempts to reverse the decision.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] In the 2011 election season, Mississippi placed an amendment on the ballot that redefined how the state viewed abortion.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] The personhood amendment defined personhood as "every human being from the moment of fertilization, cloning or the functional equivalent thereof"; if passed, it would have been illegal to get an abortion in the state.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] On July 11, 2012, a Mississippi federal judge ordered an extension of his temporary order to allow the state's only abortion clinic to stay open.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] The order was to stay in place until U.S.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] District Judge Daniel Porter Jordan III could review newly drafted rules on how the Mississippi Department of Health would administer a new abortion law.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] The law in question came into effect on July 1, 2012.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] Between 2008 and 2016, the Turnaway Study followed a group of 1,000 women, two of whom died after giving birth, for five years after they sought an abortion, and compared their health and socio-economic consequences of receiving an abortion or being denied one.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] The study found that those who were provided with abortion performed better, and those who were denied one suffered negative consequences.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] *Scientific American* described it as landmark.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] A follow-up Turnaway Study was confirmed to determinate the health and economic impact of *Roe* being overturned, which other scholars also analyzed.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] Jackson Women's Health Organization* case, which confirmed the May 2022 leaks obtained by *Politico* and overruled *Roe* and *Planned Parenthood v.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] The American Historical Association (AHA) and the Organization of American Historians (OAH) were among those who signed an *amici curiae* brief for *Dobbs*, and were cited, among others, by *Reason*, *Syracuse University News*, and *The Washington Post*.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] Joined by at least 30 other academic and scholarly institutions, they condemned "the court's misinterpretation about the history of legalized abortion" and said it has "the potential to exacerbate historic injustices and deepen inequalities in our country".
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] In the wake of state abortion bans and restrictions in the United States, Americans have started traveling to Mexico for abortions, and Mexico has expressed a willingness to help.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] Providers openly treat American travelers in several states where abortion remains technically illegal, such as Nuevo Leon, which neighbors Texas.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] Following the Supreme Court ruling, abortion is being gradually legalized at the state level, and as of 2025 is legal during the first trimester (before the 13th week after implantation) in twenty states and Mexico City.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] Although it is uncommon, women sometimes give birth in spite of an attempted abortion.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/abortion-in-the-united-states-p03] Reporting of live birth after attempted abortion may not be consistent from state to state, but 38 were recorded in one study in upstate New York in the two-and-a-half years before *Roe v.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/academic-degree-p01] An **academic degree** is a qualification awarded to a student upon successful completion of a course of study in higher education.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/academic-degree-p01] Academic degrees are commonly structured in levels, most often categorized as undergraduate and postgraduate degrees.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/academic-degree-p01] The most common undergraduate qualification is the bachelor's degree, although some educational systems also offer lower-level degrees such as the associate degree or the foundation degree.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/academic-degree-p01] Postgraduate degrees include the engineer's degree, the master's degree, and the doctorate.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/academic-degree-p01] In the UK and countries whose educational systems are based on the British system, honours degrees are divided into classes: first, second (broken into upper second, or 2.1, and lower second, or 2.2) and third class.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/academic-degree-p01] The doctorate (Latin: *doceo*, "I teach") first appeared in medieval Europe as a license to teach (Latin: *licentia docendi*) at a medieval university.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/academic-degree-p01] Its roots can be traced to the early church when the term "doctor" referred to the Apostles, Church Fathers and other Christian authorities who taught and interpreted the Bible.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/academic-degree-p01] The right to grant a *licentia docendi* was originally reserved by the church which required the applicant to pass a test, take an oath of allegiance, and pay a fee.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/academic-degree-p01] The Third Council of the Lateran of 1179 guaranteed the access – now largely free of charge – of all able applicants, who were, however, still tested for aptitude by the ecclesiastic scholastic.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/academic-degree-p01] This right remained a point of contention between the church authorities and the slowly emancipating universities, but was granted by the Pope to the University of Paris in 1231 where it became a universal license to teach (*licentia ubique docendi*).
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/academic-degree-p01] While the *licentia* continued to hold a higher prestige than the bachelor's degree (*Baccalaureus*), it was ultimately reduced to an intermediate step to the Magister and doctorate, both of which now became the exclusive qualification for teaching.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/academic-degree-p01] In universities, doctoral training was a form of apprenticeship to a guild.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/academic-degree-p01] The traditional term of study before new teachers were admitted to the guild of "Master of Arts" was seven years.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/academic-degree-p01] This was the same as the term of apprenticeship for other occupations.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/academic-degree-p01] Originally the terms "master" and "doctor" were synonymous, but over time the doctorate came to be regarded as a higher qualification than the master's degree.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/academic-degree-p01] Today the terms "master" (from the Latin *magister*, lit.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/academic-degree-p01] 'teacher'), "Doctor", and "Professor" signify different levels of academic achievement, but in the Medieval university, they were equivalent terms.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/academic-degree-p01] The use of them in the degree name was a matter of custom at a university.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/academic-degree-p01] Most universities conferred the Master of Arts, although the highest degree was often termed Master of Theology/Divinity or Doctor of Theology/Divinity, depending on the place.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/academic-degree-p01] The earliest doctoral degrees (theology – *Divinitatis* Doctor (D.D.), law – *Legum* Doctor (LL.D., later D.C.L.) and medicine – *Medicinæ* Doctor (M.D., D.M.)) reflected the historical separation of all higher university study into these three fields.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/academic-degree-p01] Over time, the D.D. has gradually become less common outside theology and is now mostly used for honorary degrees, with the title "Doctor of Theology" being used more often for earned degrees.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/academic-degree-p01] Studies outside theology, law, and medicine were then called "philosophy", due to the Renaissance conviction that real knowledge could be derived from empirical observation.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/academic-degree-p01] The degree title of Doctor of Philosophy is a much later creation and was not introduced in England before 1900.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/academic-degree-p01] Studies in what once was called philosophy are now classified as sciences and humanities.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/academic-degree-p01] George Makdisi theorizes that the *ijazah* issued in medieval Islamic madrasas in the 9th century was the origin of the doctorate that later appeared in medieval European universities.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/academic-degree-p01] Alfred Guillaume, Syed Farid al-Attas and Devin J.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/academic-degree-p01] Stewart agree that there is a resemblance between the *ijazah* and the university degree.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/academic-degree-p01] However, Toby Huff and others reject Makdisi's theory.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/academic-degree-p01] Stewart finds that the *ijazat al-ifta*, license to teach Islamic law and issue legal opinions, is most similar to the medieval European university degree in that it permits entry into certain professions.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/academic-degree-p01] A key difference was that the granting authority of the *ijaza* was an individual professor whereas the university degree was granted by a corporate entity.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/academic-degree-p01] The University of Bologna in Italy, regarded as the oldest university in Europe, was the first institution to confer the degree of Doctor in Civil Law in the late 12th century; it also conferred similar degrees in other subjects, including medicine.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/academic-degree-p01] The University of Paris used the term "master" for its graduates, a practice adopted by the English universities of Oxford and Cambridge, as well as the ancient Scottish universities of St Andrews, Glasgow, Aberdeen and Edinburgh.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/academic-degree-p01] The term "bachelor" comes from the Latin *baccalaureus*, a term previously used to describe a squire (i.e., apprentice) to a knight.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/academic-degree-p01] Further study and, in particular, successful participation in, and moderation of, disputations would earn one the Master of Arts degree, from the Latin magister, "master" (typically indicating a teacher), entitling one to teach these subjects.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/academic-degree-p01] Masters of Arts were eligible to enter study under the "higher faculties" of Law, Medicine or Theology and earn first a bachelor's and then master's or doctor's degree in these subjects.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/academic-degree-p01] Thus, a degree was only a step on the way to becoming a fully qualified master – hence the English word "graduate", which is based on the Latin *gradus* ("step").
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/academic-degree-p01] The naming of degrees eventually became linked to the subjects studied.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/academic-degree-p01] Scholars in the faculties of arts or grammar became known as "masters", but those in theology, medicine and law were known as "doctors".
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/academic-degree-p01] As a study in the arts or grammar was a necessary prerequisite to study in subjects such as theology, medicine and law, the degree of doctor assumed a higher status than the master's degree.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/academic-degree-p01] This led to the modern hierarchy in which the Doctor of Philosophy (Ph.D.), which in its present form as a degree based on research and dissertation is a development from 18th- and 19th-century German universities, is a more advanced degree than the Master of Arts (M.A.).
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/academic-degree-p01] The practice of using the term *doctor* for PhDs developed within German universities and spread across the academic world.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/academic-degree-p01] The French terminology is tied closely to the original meanings of the terms.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/academic-degree-p01] "bachelor") is conferred upon French students who have completed their secondary education and allows the student to attend university.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/academic-degree-p01] When students graduate from university, they are awarded a *licence*, much as the medieval teaching guilds would have done, and they are qualified to teach in secondary schools or proceed to higher-level studies.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/academic-degree-p01] Spain had a similar structure: the term *"Bachiller"* was used for those who finished the secondary or high-school level education, known as *"Bachillerato"*.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/academic-degree-p01] The standard Spanish university 5-year degree was *"Licenciado"*, (although there were a few 3-year associate degrees called *"diplomaturas"*, from where the *"diplomados"* could move to study a related *licenciatura*).
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/academic-degree-p01] In the past, degrees have been directly issued by the authority of the monarch or by a bishop, rather than any educational institution.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/academic-degree-p01] In Great Britain, Lambeth degrees are still awarded by the Archbishop of Canterbury.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/academic-degree-p01] The Archbishop of Canterbury's right to grant degrees is derived from the Peter's Pence Act 1533, which empowered the Archbishop to grant dispensations previously granted by the Pope.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/academic-degree-p01] Among educational institutions, St David's College, Lampeter, was granted limited degree awarding powers by royal charter in the nineteenth century, despite not being a university.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/academic-degree-p01] The University College of North Staffordshire was also granted degree awarding powers on its foundation in 1949, despite not becoming a university (as the University of Keele) until 1962.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/academic-degree-p01] Following the Education Reform Act 1988, many educational institutions other than universities have been granted degree-awarding powers, including higher education colleges and colleges of the University of London, many of which are now effectively universities in their own right.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/academic-degree-p01] In many countries, gaining an academic degree entitles the holder to assume distinctive academic dress particular to the awarding institution, identifying the status of the individual wearing them.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/academic-degree-p01] In many countries, degrees may only be awarded by institutions authorised to do so by the national or regional government.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/academic-degree-p01] Frequently, governments will also regulate the use of the word *university* in the names of businesses.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/academic-degree-p01] This approach is followed, for example, by Australia, the United Kingdom and Israel.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/academic-degree-p01] The use of fake degrees by individuals, either obtained from a bogus institution or simply invented, is often covered by fraud laws.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/academic-degree-p01] Depending on the culture and the degree earned, degrees may be indicated by a pre-nominal title, post-nominal letters, a choice of either, or not indicated at all.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/academic-degree-p01] In countries influenced by the UK, post-nominal letters are the norm, with only doctorates granting a title, while titles are the norm in many northern European countries.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/academic-degree-p01] Depending on the culture and the purpose of the listing, only the highest degree, a selection of degrees, or all degrees might be listed.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/academic-degree-p01] The awarding institution may be shown and it might be specified if a degree was at honours level, particularly where the honours degree is a separate qualification from the ordinary bachelor's degree.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/academic-degree-p01] For member institutions of the Association of Commonwealth Universities, there is a standard list of abbreviations for university names given in the Commonwealth Universities Yearbook.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/academic-degree-p01] In practice, many variations are used and the Yearbook notes that the abbreviations used may not match those used by the universities concerned.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/academic-degree-p01] Other Latin abbreviations commonly used include 'Cantuar' for Lambeth degrees (awarded by the Archbishop of Canterbury), 'Dunelm' for Durham University, 'Ebor' for the University of York and 'Exon' for the University of Exeter.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/academic-degree-p01] The Ancient universities of Scotland and the University of London have abbreviations that are the same in English and Latin.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/academic-degree-p01] Confusion can result from universities sharing similar names, e.g. the University of York in the UK and York University in Canada or Newcastle University in the UK and the University of Newcastle in Australia.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/academic-degree-p01] In this case, the convention is to include a country abbreviation with the university's name.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/academic-degree-p01] For example, 'York (Can.)' and 'York (UK)' or 'Newc (UK)' and 'Newc (Aus.) are commonly used to denote degrees conferred by these universities where the potential for confusion exists, and institution names are given in this form in the Commonwealth Universities Yearbook.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/academic-degree-p01] Abbreviations used for degrees vary between countries and institutions, e.g.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/academic-degree-p01] MS indicates Master of Science in the US and places following American usage, but Master of Surgery in the UK and most Commonwealth countries, where the standard abbreviation for Master of Science is MSc.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/academic-degree-p01] Common abbreviations include BA and MA for Bachelor and Master of Arts, BS/BSc and MS/MSc for Bachelor and Master of Science, MD for Doctor of Medicine and PhD for Doctor of Philosophy.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/academic-degree-p01] Improvements in technology, the increasing use of the Internet worldwide, and the need for people to have flexible school schedules that enable them to work while attending school have led to a proliferation of online colleges that award associate's, bachelor's, master's, and doctoral degrees.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/academic-degree-p02] Bangladesh and India mostly follow the colonial era British system for the classification of degrees, however, Pakistan has recently switched to the US model of a two-year associate degree and a four-year bachelor's degree program.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/academic-degree-p02] The arts, referring to the performing arts and literature, may confer a Bachelor of Arts (BA) and a Master of Arts (MA).
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/academic-degree-p02] Management degrees are also classified under 'arts' but are nowadays considered a separate stream, with degrees of Bachelor of Business Administration (BBA) and Master of Business Administration (MBA).
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/academic-degree-p02] Science refers to the basic sciences and natural science (Biology, Physics, Chemistry, etc.); the corresponding degrees are Bachelor of Science (BSc) and Master of Science (MSc).
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/academic-degree-p02] Information Technology degrees are conferred specially in the field of computer science, and include Bachelor of Science in Information Technology (B.Sc.IT.) and Master of Science in Information Technology (M.Sc.IT.).
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/academic-degree-p02] The engineering degree in India follows two nomenclatures, Bachelor of Engineering (B.Eng.) and Bachelor of Technology (B.Tech.).
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/academic-degree-p02] Both represent bachelor's degree in engineering.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/academic-degree-p02] In Pakistan, engineering degrees are Bachelor of Engineering (B.E.) and Bachelor of Science in Engineering (B.S./B.Sc.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/academic-degree-p02] Both are the same in curriculum, duration and pattern, and differ only in nomenclature.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/academic-degree-p02] The engineering degree in Bangladesh is a Bachelor of Science in Engineering (B.Sc.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/academic-degree-p02] Indonesia follows a higher education system that originated from the Dutch colonial period.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/academic-degree-p02] However, over the years, Indonesia has transitioned from the Dutch degree classification system and developed its own academic distinctions by translating and adapting its degree structure.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/academic-degree-p02] All degrees in Indonesia follow standardized regulations.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/academic-degree-p02] The duration of each program is specified by Regulation of the Minister of Education and Culture of the Republic of Indonesia Number 3 of 2020 on National Standards of Higher Education.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/academic-degree-p02] The regulation outlines the maximum duration and minimum credit requirements (Semester Credit Units or SKS) for each level of study without counting academic leave.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/academic-degree-p02] The degree structure follows a standardized pattern, where XX represents the specific field of study.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/academic-degree-p02] Since a semester consists of 14 or 15 weeks of coursework and 1 or 2 weeks of exams, one SKS translates to an average of 40 hours of study per semester.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/academic-degree-p02] Comparatively, one European Credit Transfer and Accumulation System (ECTS) credit equals 28 hours of study, meaning that one Indonesian SKS is approximately equivalent to 1.5 ECTS.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/academic-degree-p02] Therefore, a bachelor's degree in Indonesia (minimum 144 SKS) is roughly equivalent to 216 ECTS, which surpasses the standard European requirement of 180 ECTS for a bachelor's degree.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/academic-degree-p02] All degrees in Indonesia grant academic titles, which are often used in formal and social settings, including on unofficial documents such as marriage invitations.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/academic-degree-p02] Before Indonesia adopted its modern degree classification, the country used a system copied from the Dutch colonial academic structure, which in Netherlands remained extant to 2002.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/academic-degree-p02] In this system, university students typically studied for five years before graduating.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/academic-degree-p02] This structure was different from the modern four-year bachelor's (S1) degree, as it allowed graduates to proceed directly to a doctorate (S3) program without first obtaining a master's (S2) degree.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/academic-degree-p02] This system included pre-nominal academic titles that have largely been phased out but are still recognized, for those who graduated before 1992.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/academic-degree-p02] Some of these titles are still in limited use today.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/academic-degree-p02] Doktorandus (Drs.) and Doktoranda (Dra.) originated from Latin, meaning "one who is to become a doctor." These titles indicated that the degree holder only needed to complete a dissertation to obtain a doctorate.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/academic-degree-p02] Until the 1960s, diplomas from Bandung Institute of Technology (ITB) explicitly stated that holders were entitled to pursue a doctorate upon defending a thesis.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/academic-degree-p02] After the 1970s, ITB replaced Doktorandus and Insinyur (Engineer) titles with Sarjana (Bachelor) degrees.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/academic-degree-p02] However, these titles remained granted and used until 1992 in other universities or institutes.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/academic-degree-p02] By aligning with Anglo education standards, Indonesia transitioned to the B.Sc. - M.Sc. - Ph.D. model, similar to the Bologna Process.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/academic-degree-p02] Unlike the previous system, where five-year graduates could proceed directly to a Ph.D., students must now complete an S1 (Bachelor's) and S2 (Master's) before pursuing S3 (Doctorate).
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/academic-degree-p02] Despite this transition, many pre-1992 graduates retained the use of their original titles granted upon their graduation, making formats such as Prof.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/academic-degree-p02] Drs. [Name] common among senior academics and professionals.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/academic-degree-p02] Sri Lanka, like many other commonwealth countries, follows the British system, but with its own distinctions.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/academic-degree-p02] Degrees are approved by the University Grants Commission.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/academic-degree-p02] Tunisia's educational grading system, ranging from elementary school to Ph.D. programs, operates on a scale of 0 to 20.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/academic-degree-p02] The minimum score for passing is set at 10 out of 20.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/academic-degree-p02] This numerical system exclusively evaluates a student's academic accomplishments, serving as the determinant for admission into advanced programs.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/academic-degree-p02] For instance, a student's grades obtained for their bachelor's degree are considered when they apply for a Master's program.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/academic-degree-p02] Level 4 courses, which include the first year of a Bachelor's program or a Higher National Certificate (HNC), may allow students to enter directly into the second year of a Bachelor's program, provided that the course they completed is the same as the one they are applying for.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/academic-degree-p02] In South Africa, grades (also known as "marks") are presented as a percentage, with anything below 50% considered a failure.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/academic-degree-p02] Students who receive a failing grade may have the opportunity to rewrite the exam, depending on the criteria established by their institution.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/academic-degree-p02] Degrees in almost any field of study can be pursued at one of the institutions in the country, with certain institutions being known for excelling in specific fields.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/academic-degree-p02] Major fields of study across the country include Arts, Commerce, Engineering, Law, Medicine, Science, and Theology.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/academic-degree-p02] The South African Qualifications Authority (SAQA) has developed a credit-based system for degrees, with different levels of National Qualifications Framework (NQF) ratings corresponding to each degree level.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/academic-degree-p02] For example, an undergraduate degree in Science is rated at NQF level 6, while an additional year of study in that discipline would result in an NQF level 8 (honours degree) rating.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/academic-degree-p02] In Kenya, the first undergraduate degree is pursued after students have completed four years of secondary school education and attained at least a C+ (55–59%) on the Kenya Certificate of Secondary Education (KCSE).
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/academic-degree-p02] Students pursuing a degree in engineering, such as B.Sc.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/academic-degree-p02] Electrical and Electronics Engineering, are required to join programs that are accredited by the Engineers Board of Kenya and the Commission for University Education.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/academic-degree-p02] The B.Sc. degree in engineering typically takes five years to complete.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/academic-degree-p02] A degree in medicine or surgery may take six to seven years, while a degree in education or management takes around four years.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/academic-degree-p02] For students pursuing a master's degree, they must have completed an undergraduate degree and attained at least a second-class honours upper division (60–69%) or lower division plus at least two years of relevant experience.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/academic-degree-p02] Most master's degree programs take two years to complete.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/academic-degree-p02] In an engineering master's degree program, students are typically required to publish at least one scientific paper in a peer-reviewed journal.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/academic-degree-p02] To pursue a doctor of philosophy degree, students must have completed a relevant master's degree.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/academic-degree-p02] They are required to carry out a supervised scientific study for a minimum of three years and publish at least two scientific first-author papers in peer-reviewed journals relevant to their area of study.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/academic-degree-p02] Currently, Kenya is implementing a Competency Based Curriculum (CBC) that follows a 2–6–3–3 education system to replace the existing 8–4–4 system which allows confirmation of undergraduate degrees upon successful completion.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/academic-degree-p02] This system is gradually replacing the two-stage system previously used in some countries and is combined with other elements such as the European Credit Transfer and Accumulation System (ECTS) and the use of Diploma Supplements to make comparisons between qualifications easier.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/academic-degree-p02] The European Higher Education Area (EHEA) was formally established in 2010 and, as of September 2016, has 50 members.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/academic-degree-p02] The implementation of the various elements of the EHEA varies between countries.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/academic-degree-p02] Twenty-four countries have fully implemented a national qualifications framework, and a further ten have a framework but have not yet certified it against the overarching framework.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/academic-degree-p02] In 38 countries, ECTS credits are used for all higher education programmes, and 31 countries have fully implemented diploma supplements.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/academic-degree-p02] Only 11 countries have included all the major points of the Lisbon Recognition Convention in national legislation.
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/academic-degree-p02] Since 2008, the European Union has been developing the European Qualifications Framework (EQF).
[src:affluence-in-the-united-states/academic-degree-p02] This is an eight-level framework designed to allow cross-referencing of the various national qualifications frameworks.
